{"title_page": "Movili\u021ba, Vrancea", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Vrancea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Vrancea County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|57|N|27|06|E|type:adm3rd_source:kolossus-itwiki|display=it}}\n|name=Movili\u021ba\n|image_map              = Movilita jud Vrancea.png\n}}\n'''Movili\u021ba''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[Vrancea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Dioche\u021bi-Rediu, Frec\u0103\u021bei, Movili\u021ba, Trotu\u0219anu and V\u0103leni.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vrancea County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Movilita, Vrancea}}\n[[Category:Communes in Vrancea County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Western Moldavia]]\n\n{{Vrancea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Vrancea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Vrancea County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|57|N|27|06|E|type:adm3rd_source:kolossus-itwiki|display=it}}\n|name=Movili\u021ba\n|image_map=\n}}\n'''Movili\u021ba''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[Vrancea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of five villages: Dioche\u021bi-Rediu, Frec\u0103\u021bei, Movili\u021ba, Trotu\u0219anu and V\u0103leni.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vrancea County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Movilita, Vrancea}}\n[[Category:Communes in Vrancea County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Western Moldavia]]\n\n{{Vrancea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Movili%C8%9Ba,_Vrancea"}
{"title_page": "Ali Akbar al-Modarresi", "text_new": "[[Grand Ayatollah|Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]] '''Ali-Akbar al-Husayni al-Modarresi''' ({{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0649 \u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0649}}}}; {{lang-ar| \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}; b. 17 September 1957) is a [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]]-[[Iraqis|Iraqi]] [[scholar]] and [[teacher]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography|name=Ali-Akbar al-Modarresi|nationality=[[Iranian peoples|Iranian]]|students=[[Nimr al-Nimr]] <br /> [[Mohammed Ridha al-Shirazi]]|denomination=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam|Sh\u012b\u02bf\u0101]]|religion=Islam|relatives=[[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]] (grandfather) <br />\n[[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Hadi al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Abd al-A'la al-Sabziwari]] (uncle-in-law)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=345|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> Muhammad-Reza Gharavi (second cousin, once removed)|website=|children=Muhammed-Ridha|death_place=|native_name={{lang|fa|\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}|death_date=|birth_place=[[Karbala]], [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]]|birth_date={{birth date and age|1957|9|17}}|caption=|image=Ali Akbar al-Modarresi.jpg|honorific-prefix=[[Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]]|background=#ABE9CC|parents=[[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi]] (father)|spouse=}}\n\n== Family ==\nal-Modarresi was born into a distinguished Shia religious family in Karbala in Iraq. His father is Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad-Kadhim al-Modarresi<ref name=\":0\" />, the grandson of grand Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad-Baqir Golpayegani (also known as ''Jorfadiqani'').<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tehrani|first=Agha Buzurg|url=http://alfeker.net/library.php?id=3324|title=Tabaqat A'lam al-Shia; al-Kiram al-Barara Fi al-Qarn al-Thalith Ashar|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2009|isbn=|volume=10|location=Cairo, Egpyt|pages=165|trans-title=Levels of the Notables of the Shia (13th Century)}}</ref> His mother is the daughter of grand Ayatollah Sayyid [[Mahdi Hussaini Shirazi|Mehdi al-Shirazi]]. He claims descent from [[Zayd ibn Ali]] (died c. 740 AD), the great-great-grandson of the [[Prophets in Islam|Islamic prophet]], [[Muhammad]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197\u20138|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n== Religious career ==\nal-Modarresi studied in the religious seminaries of Karbala, under his father, Sayyid Muhammad-Kadhim and brother Sayyid [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Taqi]], as well as senior scholars such as Shaykh Muhammad-Husayn al-Mazindarani, Shaykh Jafar al-Rushti, and his maternal uncles Sayyid [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]] and Sayyid Hassan al-Shirazi.<ref name=\":02\" /> He emigrated to Kuwait with his older brothers in 1971, due to the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathists]] anti-Shia sentiment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2013-03-20/saddam-husseins-legacy-sectarian-division-iraq|title=Saddam Hussein's legacy of sectarian division in Iraq|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/iraqs-oppressed-majority-95250996/|title=Iraq's Oppressed Majority|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> They settled there until 1979, after which they moved to Iran after the [[Iranian Revolution|Islamic Revolution]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=al-Jibouri|first=Kamil Salman|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KD8-CwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT364&dq|title=Mu'jam al-'Udaba' Min 'Asr al-Jahili Hata Sanat 2002|publisher=Daar al-Kitab al-'Ilmiya|year=2003|isbn=|volume=5|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=180\u20131|language=Arabic|trans-title=Glossary of Scholars: From the Jahiliyyah to 2002 AD}}</ref>\n\nal-Modarresi taught in al-Qaim seminary, which was established by his brother Muhammad-Taqi, in 1980, until it was closed down in 1990. He remained in [[Tehran]] whilst his brothers went to [[Syria]],<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Lobad|first=Adil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4E5HAQAAIAAJ&q|title=al-Inqilab, Bay' al-Qiyam 'Alal Thaat|date=|publisher=Laila for Publishing & Distributing|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=339\u201340|language=Arabic|trans-title=Coups, Selling Morals For Ego}}</ref> teaching in different religious seminaries, until he moved to [[Mashhad]] in 2014, and began teaching at its seminary, near the shrine of [[Ali al-Ridha|Imam al-Ridha]].\n\nDuring his time in al-Qaim, al-Modarresi taught distinguished [[Saudis|Saudi]] activist [[Nimr al-Nimr]] and was considered as his mentor. He had a close relationship with him even after the closure of the seminary, until his execution in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ar.imam-khomeini.ir/ar/n14843/\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631/\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e_\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0645\u0631_\u0634\u0647\u064a\u062f\u064b\u0627_|title=al-Shaykh al-Nimr Shaheedan|last=|first=|date=|website=Imam Khomeini Cultural Foundation|language=Arabic|trans-title=Shaykh Nimr is a martyr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TheSayed/status/819837957637107712|title=\u0623\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0630 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0648\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u062f\u0633\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0622\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a\u060c \u0644\u064a\u0633 \u0634\u062e\u0635\u064a\u0629 \u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629\u060c \u0644\u0643\u0646 \u064a\u0643\u0641\u064a\u0647 \u0641\u0636\u0644\u0627\u064b \u0623\u0646\u0647 \u0623\u062d\u062f \u0623\u0633\u0627\u062a\u0630\u0629 \u0622\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 #\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u064a\u062f_\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0645\u0631pic.twitter.com/TeaxSKVjzc|last=al-Modarresi|first=al-Sayyid Mehdi|date=2017-01-13|website=@TheSayed|language=ar|trans-title=Teacher at the holy seminary, Ayatollah Sayyid Ali Akbar al-Modarresi, is not a media personality, but it is enough that he was one of the teachers of the martyr Ayatollah Nimr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nal-Modarresi is married to the daughter of prominent scholar, Baqir al-Qazwini (d. 1974).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ScQ-AQAAIAAJ|title=Mashahir al-Madfunin Fi Karbala|date=2009|publisher=Dar al-Safwa|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=109|language=ar|trans-title=Famous Figures Buried In Karbala}}</ref> \n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]]\n* [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Mohammed Taqi al-Modarresi]]\n* [[Nimr al-Nimr]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Muslim activists]]\n[[Category:Iraqi people]]\n[[Category:Islamic studies scholars]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[Grand Ayatollah|Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]] '''Ali-Akbar al-Husayni al-Modarresi''' ({{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0649 \u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0649}}}}; {{lang-ar| \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}; b. 17 September 1957) is a [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]]-[[Iraqis|Iraqi]] [[scholar]] and [[teacher]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography|name=Ali-Akbar al-Modarresi|nationality=[[Iranian peoples|Iranian]]|students=[[Nimr al-Nimr]] <br /> [[Mohammed Ridha al-Shirazi]]|denomination=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam|Sh\u012b\u02bf\u0101]]|religion=Islam|relatives=[[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]] (grandfather) <br />\n[[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Hadi al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Abd al-A'la al-Sabziwari]] (uncle-in-law)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=345|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> Muhammad-Reza Gharavi (second cousin, once removed)|website=|children=Muhammed-Ridha|death_place=|native_name={{lang|fa|\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}|death_date=|birth_place=[[Karbala]], [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]]|birth_date={{birth date and age|1957|9|17}}|caption=|image=Ali Akbar al-Modarresi.jpg|honorific-prefix=[[Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]]|background=#ABE9CC|parents=[[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi]]|spouse=}}\n\n== Family ==\nal-Modarresi was born into a distinguished Shia religious family in Karbala in Iraq. His father is Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad-Kadhim al-Modarresi<ref name=\":0\" />, the grandson of grand Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad-Baqir Golpayegani (also known as ''Jorfadiqani'').<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tehrani|first=Agha Buzurg|url=http://alfeker.net/library.php?id=3324|title=Tabaqat A'lam al-Shia; al-Kiram al-Barara Fi al-Qarn al-Thalith Ashar|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2009|isbn=|volume=10|location=Cairo, Egpyt|pages=165|trans-title=Levels of the Notables of the Shia (13th Century)}}</ref> His mother is the daughter of grand Ayatollah Sayyid [[Mahdi Hussaini Shirazi|Mehdi al-Shirazi]]. He claims descent from [[Zayd ibn Ali]] (died c. 740 AD), the great-great-grandson of the [[Prophets in Islam|Islamic prophet]], [[Muhammad]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197\u20138|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n== Religious career ==\nal-Modarresi studied in the religious seminaries of Karbala, under his father, Sayyid Muhammad-Kadhim and brother Sayyid [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Taqi]], as well as senior scholars such as Shaykh Muhammad-Husayn al-Mazindarani, Shaykh Jafar al-Rushti, and his maternal uncles Sayyid [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]] and Sayyid Hassan al-Shirazi.<ref name=\":02\" /> He emigrated to Kuwait with his older brothers in 1971, due to the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathists]] anti-Shia sentiment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2013-03-20/saddam-husseins-legacy-sectarian-division-iraq|title=Saddam Hussein's legacy of sectarian division in Iraq|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/iraqs-oppressed-majority-95250996/|title=Iraq's Oppressed Majority|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> They settled there until 1979, after which they moved to Iran after the [[Iranian Revolution|Islamic Revolution]].<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|last=al-Jibouri|first=Kamil Salman|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KD8-CwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT364&dq|title=Mu'jam al-'Udaba' Min 'Asr al-Jahili Hata Sanat 2002|publisher=Daar al-Kitab al-'Ilmiya|year=2003|isbn=|volume=5|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=180\u20131|language=Arabic|trans-title=Glossary of Scholars: From the Jahiliyyah to 2002 AD}}</ref>\n\nal-Modarresi taught in al-Qaim seminary, which was established by his brother Muhammad-Taqi, in 1980, until it was closed down in 1990. He remained in [[Tehran]] whilst his brothers went to [[Syria]],<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Lobad|first=Adil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4E5HAQAAIAAJ&q|title=al-Inqilab, Bay' al-Qiyam 'Alal Thaat|date=|publisher=Laila for Publishing & Distributing|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=339\u201340|language=Arabic|trans-title=Coups, Selling Morals For Ego}}</ref> teaching in different religious seminaries, until he moved to [[Mashhad]] in 2014, and began teaching at its seminary, near the shrine of [[Ali al-Ridha|Imam al-Ridha]].\n\nDuring his time in al-Qaim, al-Modarresi taught distinguished [[Saudis|Saudi]] activist [[Nimr al-Nimr]] and was considered as his mentor. He had a close relationship with him even after the closure of the seminary, until his execution in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ar.imam-khomeini.ir/ar/n14843/\u0623\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631/\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e_\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0645\u0631_\u0634\u0647\u064a\u062f\u064b\u0627_|title=al-Shaykh al-Nimr Shaheedan|last=|first=|date=|website=Imam Khomeini Cultural Foundation|language=Arabic|trans-title=Shaykh Nimr is a martyr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TheSayed/status/819837957637107712|title=\u0623\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0630 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0648\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u062f\u0633\u0629 \u0633\u0645\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0622\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0623\u0643\u0628\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a\u060c \u0644\u064a\u0633 \u0634\u062e\u0635\u064a\u0629 \u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629\u060c \u0644\u0643\u0646 \u064a\u0643\u0641\u064a\u0647 \u0641\u0636\u0644\u0627\u064b \u0623\u0646\u0647 \u0623\u062d\u062f \u0623\u0633\u0627\u062a\u0630\u0629 \u0622\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 #\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u064a\u062f_\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0645\u0631pic.twitter.com/TeaxSKVjzc|last=al-Modarresi|first=al-Sayyid Mehdi|date=2017-01-13|website=@TheSayed|language=ar|trans-title=Teacher at the holy seminary, Ayatollah Sayyid Ali Akbar al-Modarresi, is not a media personality, but it is enough that he was one of the teachers of the martyr Ayatollah Nimr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nal-Modarresi is married to the daughter of prominent scholar, Baqir al-Qazwini (d. 1974).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ScQ-AQAAIAAJ|title=Mashahir al-Madfunin Fi Karbala|date=2009|publisher=Dar al-Safwa|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=109|language=ar|trans-title=Famous Figures Buried In Karbala}}</ref> \n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]]\n* [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Mohammed Taqi al-Modarresi]]\n* [[Nimr al-Nimr]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Muslim activists]]\n[[Category:Iraqi people]]\n[[Category:Islamic studies scholars]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Sourceofgrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox info added.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_Akbar_al-Modarresi"}
{"title_page": "Sita", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| type = Hindu\n| image = File:Sitas Exile by Raja Ravi Varma (1848 - 1906).jpg\n| caption = Sita in exile by [[Raja Ravi Varma]].\n| name = Sita\n| Devanagari = \u0938\u0940\u0924\u093e\n| Sanskrit_transliteration = S\u012bt\u0101\n| affiliation = [[Avatar]] of [[Lakshmi]], [[Devi]], [[Panchakanya]]\n|dynasty =[[Kingdom of the Videhas|Videha]] ''(by birth)''<br />[[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]] ''(by marriage)''\n| consort = [[Rama]]\n| children = [[Luv (Ramayana)|Lava]] (son) <br /> [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] (son)\n| father = [[Janaka]]\n| mother= Sunaina\n| siblings = [[Urmila]] (sister)<br> [[Mandavi]] <br> [[Shrutakirti]] (cousins)\n| texts = ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]\n| festivals = Sita Navami, Janaki Jayanti, [[Vivaha Panchami]], [[Diwali]], [[Dussehra]]\n| birth_place = [[Mithila (region)|Mithila]]{{efn|Either present-day [[Sitamarhi district]], [[Bihar]], [[India]] <ref>https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/rs-48-5-crore-for-sita-s-birthplace/cid/1440819</ref><ref name=\"telegraphindia.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/hot-spring-hot-spot-fair-begins-on-magh-full-moon-s-day/cid/1544104|title=Hot spring hot spot - Fair begins on Magh full moon's day|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sitamarhi\">{{cite encyclopedia | url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/546790/Sitamarhi | title=Sitamarhi | encyclopedia=Britannica | accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Sitamarhi\">{{cite web | url=http://sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/profile/index.htm | title=History of Sitamarhi | publisher=Official site of Sitamarhi district | accessdate=30 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220171523/http://sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/profile/index.htm | archive-date=20 December 2014 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> or Present-day [[Janakpur]], [[Province No. 2]], [[Nepal]]<ref>http://sacredsites.com/asia/nepal/janakpur.html</ref>}}}}\n{{Vaishnavism}}\n\n'''Sita''' is the central female character and one of the central figures in the Hindu epic,  ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]. She is described as the daughter of the earth goddess, [[Bh\u016bmi]] or [[Prithvi]] and the adopted daughter of King [[Janaka]] of [[Videha]] and his wife, Queen Sunaina. She has a younger sister, [[Urmila]], and the female cousins [[Mandavi]] and [[Shrutakirti]].<ref name=\"Sutherland AOS\">{{cite web|last=Sutherland|first=Sally J.|title=Sita and Draupadi, Aggressive Behavior and Female Role-Models in the Sanskrit Epics|url=http://sseas.berkeley.edu/sites/default/files/faculty/files/sita_and_draupadi.pdf|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|accessdate=1 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Parmeshwaranand\">{{cite book|author=Swami Parmeshwaranand|title=Encyclopaedic Dictionaries of Puranas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FdIkaccgneAC&pg=PA1210|accessdate=31 July 2012|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-226-3|pages=1210\u20131220|date=2001-01-01}}</ref> Sita is known for her dedication, self-sacrifice, courage and purity.\n\nSita, in her youth, chooses Rama, the prince of [[Ayodhya]] as her husband in a swayamvara\u2014bride choosing the best from a crowd of suitors after a contest, where Rama proves his heroism and valor and martial power and \"defeats\" the other seekers for Seeta's hand in marriage. After the swayamvara,  she accompanies her husband to his kingdom, but later chooses to accompany her husband, along with her brother-in-law [[Lakshmana]], in his exile. While in exile, the trio settles in the [[Dandaka]] forest from where she is abducted by [[Ravana]], the [[Rakshasa]] king of [[Lanka]]. She is imprisoned in [[Ashoka Vatika]] in Lanka until she is rescued by Rama, who slays her captor. After the war, in some versions of the epic, Rama asks Sita to undergo Agni Pariksha (an [[Trial by ordeal#By fire|ordeal of fire]]) by which she proves her purity before she is accepted by Rama, which for the first time makes his brother Lakshmana get angry at him.\n\nIn some versions of the epic, the fire-god&nbsp;[[Agni]]&nbsp;creates [[Maya Sita]], who takes Sita's place and is abducted by Ravana and suffers his captivity, while the real Sita hides in the fire. During the Agni Pariksha, Maya Sita and the real Sita exchange places again. While some texts say that Maya Sita is destroyed in the flames of Agni Pariksha, others narrate how she is blessed and reborn as the epic heroine&nbsp;[[Draupadi]]&nbsp;or the goddess&nbsp;[[Alamelu|Padmavati]]. Some scriptures also mention her previous birth being&nbsp;[[Vedavati]], a woman Ravana tries to molest. {{citation needed|date=August 2017}} After proving her purity, Rama and Sita return to Ayodhya, where they are crowned as king and queen. After a few months, Sita becomes pregnant, to which a washerman makes insensitive comments on Sita to his wife, which Rama in disguise hears. Rama then sends Sita away on exile. Lakshmana is the one who leaves Sita in the forests near sage&nbsp;[[Valmiki]]'s ashram. Years later, Sita returns to the womb of her mother, the Earth, for release from a cruel world as a testimony of her purity after she reunites her two sons [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] and [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lava]] with their father Rama.<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/78 78]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology and other names==\n[[File:Indischer Maler von 1780 001.jpg|thumb|Rama and Sita in the forest by an Indian painter from 1780]]\nThe goddess is best known by the name \"Sita\", derived from the Sanskrit word ''s\u012bta'', [[furrow]].<ref name=\"Chandra1998\">{{cite book|author=Suresh Chandra|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindu Gods and Goddesses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfTE6kpz6XEC&pg=PA304|accessdate=1 August 2012|year=1998|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-039-9|pages=304\u2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Ramayana'', Janaka found her while ploughing as a part of a [[yagna]] and adopted her. The word ''S\u012bta'' was a poetic term, its imagery redolent of fecundity and the many blessings coming from settled agriculture. The Sita of the ''Ramayana'' may have been named after a more ancient [[Rigvedic deities|Vedic goddess]] Sita, who is mentioned once in the [[Rigveda]] as an earth goddess who blesses the land with good crops. In the [[Vedic period]], she was one of the goddesses associated with fertility. A Vedic hymn ([[s:The Rig Veda/Mandala 4/Hymn 57|Rig Veda 4:57]]) recites:\n{{cquote|''Auspicious Sita, come thou near;''\n''We venerate and worship thee'' <br />\n''That thou mayst bless and prosper us'' <br />\n''And bring us fruits abundantly.'' <br /> ''}}\n\nIn ''[[Harivamsa]]'', Sita is invoked as one of the names of the goddess Arya:\n{{cquote|''O goddess, you are the altar's center in the sacrifice,'' <br />\n''The priest's fee'' <br />\n''Sita to those who hold the plough'' <br />\n''And Earth to all living being. ''}}\n\nThe ''Kausik-sutra'' and the ''Paraskara-sutra'' associate her repeatedly as the wife of [[Parjanya]] (a god associated with rains) and [[Indra]].<ref name=\"Chandra1998\"/>\n\nSita is known by many epithets. She is called ''J\u0101naki'' as the daughter of Janaka and ''Maithili'' as the princess of Mithila.<ref name=Pauwels2007 /> As the wife of Rama, she is called ''Ram\u0101''. Her father Janaka had earned the sobriquet ''Videha'' due to his ability to transcend body consciousness; Sita is therefore also known as ''Vaidehi''.<ref name=\"Pauwels2007\">{{cite book|author=Heidi Rika Maria Pauwels|title=Indian Literature and Popular Cinema: Recasting Classics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LiXU4ihgMpgC&pg=PA53|accessdate=31 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-44741-6|pages=53\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDevi Sita while playing with her sisters in childhood had unknowingly lifted the table over which the bow had been placed; this was something that no one in Mithila could do. This incident was however observed by Janaka and he decided to make it a backdrop for Swayamvara because he wanted a son-in-law who was as strong as his daughter.<ref>\"https://m.dailyhunt.in/news/india/english/wittyfeed+india-epaper-witty/12+mythological+facts+about+sita+that+most+of+us+don+t+know-newsid-72197999\"</ref>\n\n==Legend==\n\n===Birth===\n[[File:Rama, Sita, Lakshmana.jpg|thumb|left|Rama, Sita and Lakshmana]]\nThe birthplace of Sita is disputed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biharlokmanch.org/indian_festivals_culture_aid_24.html|title=Bihar times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019153403/http://www.biharlokmanch.org/indian_festivals_culture_aid_24.html|archivedate=19 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Sita Kund]]<ref name=\"telegraphindia.com\"/> pilgrimage site which is located in present-day [[Sitamarhi district]],<ref name=\"Sitamarhi\"/><ref name=\"History of Sitamarhi\"/>[[Bihar]], [[India]] is viewed as the birthplace of Sita. Apart from Sitamarhi, [[Janakpur]] which is located in the present-day [[Province No. 2]], [[Nepal]],<ref name=\"m.timesofindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Modis-visit-to-Sitas-birthplace-in-Nepal-cancelled/articleshow/45220742.cms|title=Narendra Modi Cancells his visit to Sita's birthplace Janakpur, Nepal}}</ref><ref name=\"sacredsites.com\">{{cite web|url=http://sacredsites.com/asia/nepal/janakpur.html|title= Birthplace of Sita in Janakpur, Asia Travels}}</ref> is also described as Sita's birthplace.\n* ''Valmiki's Ramayana'': In Valmiki's Ramayana and its Tamil version Kamban's Ramavataram, Sita is said to have been discovered in a furrow in a ploughed field, believed to be [[Sitamarhi]] in [[Mithila (region)|Mithila region]] of present-day [[Bihar]], and for that reason is regarded as a daughter of [[Bh\u016bmi]] Devi<ref>{{cite web|title=The Story of Mother Sita the consort of Rama|url=http://www.salagram.net/parishad131.html|publisher=Salagram.net|accessdate=18 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530135807/http://salagram.net/parishad131.html|archivedate=30 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> (the goddess earth). She was discovered, adopted and brought up by [[Janaka]], king of [[History of Mithila|Mithila]] and his wife Sunaina.\n* ''Ramayana Manjari'': In ''Ramayana Manjari'' (verses 344\u2013366), North-western and Bengal recensions of Valmiki Ramayana, it has been described as on hearing a voice from the sky and then seeing [[Menaka]], Janaka expresses his wish to obtain a child, and when he finds the child, he hears the same voice again telling him the infant is his Spiritual child, born of Menaka.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n* ''Janka's real daughter'': In ''Ramopkhyana'' of the [[Mahabharata]] and also in ''Paumachariya'' of Vimala Suri, Sita has been depicted as Janaka's real daughter. According to Rev. Fr. [[Camille Bulcke]], this motif that Sita was the real daughter of Janaka, as described in ''Ramopkhyana Mahabharata'' was based on the authentic version of ''Valmiki Ramayana.'' Later, the story of Sita miraculously appearing in a furrow was inserted in ''Valmiki Ramayana''.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n* ''Reincarnation of [[Vedavati]]'': Some versions of the ''Ramayana'' suggest that Sita was a reincarnation of Vedavati. [[Ravana]] tried to molest Vedavati and her chastity was sullied beyond Ravana's redemption when she was performing penance to become the consort of Vishnu. Vedavati immolated herself on a pyre to escape Ravana's lust, vowing to return in another age and be the cause of Ravana's destruction. She was duly reborn as Sita.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n* ''Reincarnation of Manivati'': According to Gunabhadra's [[Uttara Purana]] of the ninth century BCE, Ravana disturbs the asceticism of Manivati, daughter of Amitavega of Alkapuri, and she pledges to take revenge on Ravana. Manivati is later reborn as the daughter of Ravana and [[Mandodari]]. But astrologers predicted the ruin of Ravana because of this child. So, Ravana orders to kill the child. Manivati is placed in a casket and buried in the ground of Mithila, where she is discovered by some of the farmers of the kingdom. Then Janaka, king of that state, adopts her.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\">{{cite journal|last=Singaravelu|first=S|title=S\u012bt\u0101's Birth and Parentage in the R\u0101ma Story|journal=Asian Folklore Studies|volume=41|issue=2|publisher=[[University of Malaya]], Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia|pages=235\u2013240|jstor=1178126|year=1982|doi=10.2307/1178126}}</ref>\n* ''Ravana's daughter'': In [[Rama in Jainism#Sanghadasa's version|Sanghadasa's Jaina version]] of Ramayana, and also in [[Adbhuta Ramayana]], Sita, entitled ''Vasudevahindi'', is born as the daughter of Ravana. According to this version, astrologers predict that first child of Vidyadhara Maya (Ravana's wife) will destroy his lineage. Thus, Ravana abandons her and orders the infant to be buried in a distant land where she is later discovered and adopted by Janaka.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n\n===Marriage===\n[[File:Rama breaking the bow to win Sita as wife.jpg|thumb|Rama breaks the bow to win Sita as wife.]]\nWhen Sita reaches adulthood, [[Janaka]] organizes a [[Swayamvara]] in [[Janakpurdham]] with the condition that Sita would marry only that person who would be able to string ''Pinaka'', the bow of the god [[Shiva]]. Janaka knew that the bow of Shiva was not even liftable, let alone stringable for ordinary mortals, and for selfish people it was not even approachable. Thus, Janaka tries to find the best husband for Sita.\n\nAt this time, [[Vishvamitra]] had brought Rama and his brother Lakshmana to the forest for the protection of sacrifice. Hearing about this ''swayamvara'', Vishvamitra asks Rama to participate in it and takes Rama and Lakshmana to the palace of Janaka in [[Janakpur]]. Janaka is greatly pleased to learn that Rama and Lakshmana are sons of Dasharatha. Next morning, in the middle of the hall, Rama lifts up the bow of Shiva with his left hand, fastens the string taut and breaks the bow in the process. However, another avatar of Vishnu, [[Parashurama]], became really angry as the bow of Shiva was broken. However, he does not realize that Rama is also an avatar of Vishnu, therefore after being informed of this, he apologizes for getting angry. Thus, Rama fulfills Janaka's condition to marry Sita. Later on [[Vivaha Panchami]], a marriage ceremony is conducted under the guidance of Satananda. Rama marries Sita, Bharata marries Mandavi, Lakshmana marries Urmila and Shatrughna marries Shrutakirti.<ref name=Parmeshwaranand />\n\n===Exile and abduction===\n[[File:Ravi Varma-Ravana Sita Jathayu.jpg|thumb|upright|Ravana cuts off Jatayu's wing while abducting Sita]]\nSome time after the wedding, [[Kaikeyi]], Rama's stepmother, compelled Dasharatha to make Bharata king, prompted by the coaxing of her maid [[Manthara]], and forced Rama to leave Ayodhya and spend a period of exile in the forests of [[Dandaka]] and later Panchavati. Sita and Lakshmana willingly renounced the comforts of the palace and joined Rama in exile. The Panchavati forest became the scene for Sita's abduction by Ravana, King of Lanka. Ravana kidnapped Sita, disguising himself as a mendicant, while Rama was away fetching a [[Maricha|golden deer]] to please her. Some versions of the ''Ramayana'' describe Sita taking refuge with the fire-god [[Agni]], while [[Maya Sita]], her illusionary double, is kidnapped by the demon-king. [[Jatayu (Ramayana)|Jatayu]], the vulture-king, tried to protect Sita but Ravana chopped off his wings. Jatayu survived long enough to inform Rama of what had happened.<ref name=\"Mani720\">Mani pp. 720-3; {{cite book | last = Mani | first = Vettam | title = Puranic Encyclopaedia: a Comprehensive Dictionary with Special Reference to the Epic and Puranic Literature | url = https://archive.org/details/puranicencyclopa00maniuoft | publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publishers | year = 1975 <!-- | location = Delhi --> | isbn = 978-0-8426-0822-0 | authorlink = Vettam Mani }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hanuman Encounters Sita in Ashokavana.jpg|thumb|left|Hanuman finds Sita in Ashokavana]]\nRavana took her back to his kingdom in Lanka and Sita was held as a prisoner in one of his palaces. During her captivity for a year in Lanka, Ravana expressed his desire for her; however, Sita refused his advances and struggled to maintain her chastity. [[Hanuman]] was sent by Rama to seek Sita and eventually succeeded in discovering Sita's whereabouts. Sita gave Hanuman her jewellery and asked him to give it to her husband. Hanuman returned across the sea to Rama.<ref name=\"Mani720\"/>\n\nSita was finally rescued by Rama, who waged a war to defeat Ravana. Upon rescue, Rama makes Sita undergo a trial by fire to prove her chastity. In some versions of ''Ramayana'', during this test the fire-god Agni appears in front of Rama and attests to Sita's purity, or hands over to him the real Sita and declares it was Maya Sita who was abducted by Ravana.<ref name=\"Mani720\"/> The Thai version of the Ramayana, however, tells of Sita walking on the fire, of her own accord, to feel clean, as opposed to jumping in it. She is not burnt, and the coals turn to lotuses.After proving that Sita is still pure, she returns to Ayodhya. But the citizens of Ayodhaya don't accept Sita and says that she is impure, and ram has to forcefully sent Sita against his wish. After 12 yrs he go backs to Sita and asks her to come back to Ayodhya. But Sita denies and says bhumi to take her inside herself.. Sita goes inside the earth and gives her sons to Rama....\n\n=The life of Sita, after exiling again and the reason of exiling according to mythology=\nThe couple came back to Ayodhya, where Rama was crowned king with Sita by his side.\n\nWhile Rama's trust and affection for Sita never wavered, it soon became evident that some people in Ayodhya could not accept Sita's long captivity under Ravana. During Rama's period of rule, an intemperate [[Dhobi|washerman]], while berating his wayward wife, declared that he was \"no pusillanimous Rama who would take his wife back after she had lived in the house of another man\". This statement was reported back to Rama, who knew that the accusation against Sita was baseless. Nevertheless, he would not let [[slander]] undermine his rule, so he sent Sita away.\n\nThus Sita was forced into exile a second time. Sita, who was pregnant, was given refuge in the hermitage of [[Valmiki]], where she delivered twin sons named [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] and [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lava]].<ref name=Parmeshwaranand /> In the hermitage, Sita raised her sons alone, as a single mother.<ref name=\"Contemporary Influence of Sita by\">{{cite web|last=Bhargava|first=Anju P.|title=Contemporary Influence of Sita by|url=http://www.infinityfoundation.com/ECITsitaframeset.htm|publisher=The Infinity Foundation|accessdate=31 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713001426/http://www.infinityfoundation.com/ECITsitaframeset.htm|archivedate=13 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They grew up to be valiant and intelligent and were eventually united with their father. Once she had witnessed the acceptance of her children by Rama, Sita sought final refuge in the arms of her mother [[Bh\u016bmi]]. Hearing her plea for release from an unjust world and from a life that had rarely been happy, the Earth dramatically split open; Bh\u016bmi appeared and took Sita away.(Abounding of Devi S\u012bta appears in Uttara K\u0101nda which is considered by some people as later added kanda).\n\nSita's exile during her pregnancy was because of a curse during her childhood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedpuran.files.wordpress.com/2011/10/padam-puran.pdf|title=Padma-puran pdf file|date=1 October 2018|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref> According to [[Padma Purana|Padma-puran]], Sita had caught a pair of divine parrots which were from Valmiki's ashram when she was young. The birds were talking about story of Sri Ram heard in [[Valmiki]] ashram which intrigued Sita. She has the ability to talk with animals. The female bird was pregnant at that time. She requested Sita to let them go and return from Valmiki's Ashram as they knew only up to their marriage but Sita only allowed her male companion to fly away but female parrot died because of separation from her companion. As a result, the male bird cursed Sita that she would suffer a similar fate of being separated from her husband during pregnancy. The male bird was reborn as the washerman.\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nSita test fires.png|Sita's fire test\nSita Bhum Pravesh.jpg|Sita returns to her mother, the Earth, as Sri Rama, her sons, and the sages watch in astonishment.\nRama and sita in pavilion.jpg|Rama and Sita from Uttara-Kanda.\n</gallery>\n\n==Speeches in the ''Ramayana''==\n[[File:Ramayana - Marriage of Rama Bharata Lakshmana and Shatrughna.jpg|thumb|250px|The marriage of the four sons of Dasharatha with the four daughters of Siradhvaja and Kushadhvaja Janakas. Rama and Sita, Lakshmana and Urmila, Bharata and Mandavi and Shatrughna with Shrutakirti.]]\nWhile the ''Ramayana'' mostly concentrates on Rama's actions, Sita also speaks many times during the exile. The first time is in the town of [[Chitrakoot Dham (Karwi)|Chitrakuta]] where she narrates an ancient story to Rama, whereby Rama promises to Sita that he will never kill anybody without provocation.\n\nThe second time Sita is shown talking prominently is when she speaks to Ravana. Ravana has come to her in the form of a mendicant and Sita tells him that he does not look like one.\n\nSome of her most prominent speeches are with Hanuman when he reaches Lanka. Hanuman wants an immediate union of Rama and Sita and thus he proposes to Sita to ride on his back. Sita refuses as she does not want to run away like a thief; instead she wants her husband Rama to come and defeat Ravana to save her.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Valmiki |first1=Ramayana |title=Sundarkanda, sarga 37 |url=https://www.valmiki.iitk.ac.in/sloka?field_kanda_tid=5&language=dv&field_sarga_value=37 |website=www.valmiki.iitk.ac.in |publisher=IIT Kanpur}}</ref>\n\n==Jain version==\n{{main|Rama in Jainism}}\n[[File:Hanuman before Rama.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Rama seated with Sita, fanned by [[Lakshmana]], while [[Hanuman]] pays his respects]]\nSita is said to be the daughter of [[Ravana]]'s queen [[Mandodari]]. It was predicted that the first child of Mandodari would bring annihilation to the family. Hence, Ravana deserted the child when she was born. The minister who was responsible for this took her in a pearl-box, placed her near a plough and told King [[Janaka]] of [[Mithila (ancient)|Mithila]] that the girl had been born from the furrow. Janaka's queen Sunaina became Sita's foster mother.\n\nThere is also a narration about Sita's brother Bhamandala. He did not know that Sita was his sister and wanted to marry her. He even wanted to abduct her. This story ends when Bhamandala, after learning that Sita is his sister, becomes a [[Jain monasticism|Jain ascetic]].\n\n==Symbolism==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Hermitage of Valmiki, Folio from the \"Nadaun\" Ramayana (Adventures of Rama) LACMA AC1999.127.45.jpg|thumb|250px|Sita in the [[hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]] of Valmiki]]\nA female deity of agricultural fertility by the name Sita was known before Valmiki's ''Ramayana'', but was overshadowed by better-known goddesses associated with fertility. According to ''Ramayana'', Sita was discovered in a furrow when Janaka was ploughing. Since Janaka was a king, it is likely that ploughing was part of a royal ritual to ensure fertility of the land. Sita is considered to be a child of Mother Earth, produced by union between the king and the land. Sita is a personification of Earth's fertility, abundance, and well-being.\n\n==Swami Vivekananda on Sita==\n[[File:Valmiki train Lava Kushas in Art of Archery.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Valmiki training Lava Kusha (sons of Rama & Sita) in the art of archery.]]\n[[Swami Vivekananda]] states that Rama is considered the type of the Absolute and Sita that of Power. Sita is the ideal of a woman in India and worshiped as God incarnate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cwsv.belurmath.org/volume_9/lectures_and_discourses/the_women_of_india.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304225348/http://cwsv.belurmath.org/volume_9/lectures_and_discourses/the_women_of_india.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Swami Vivekananda, Sita is typical of India \u2013 the idealized India. Swami Vivekananda assured that if world literature of the past and world literature of the future were thoroughly exhausted, yet, it would not be possible to find another Sita, because Sita is unique; the character was depicted once for all. Swami Vivekananda felt there may have been several Ramas, perhaps, but never more than one Sita.\n\nVivekananda said:\n\n{{Quote|All our mythology may vanish, even our Vedas may depart and our Sanskrit language may vanish forever, but so long as there will be five Hindus living here, even if only seeking the most vulgar patois, there will be the story of Sita present.}}\n\nSita was a true Indian by nature, Vivekananda concluded, who never returned injury.<ref>The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda/Volume 4/Lectures and Discourses/The Ramayana</ref>\n\n==Portrayal==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Srisita ram laxman hanuman manor.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Deities Sita (far right), Rama (center), Lakshmana (far left) and Hanuman (below, seated) at [[Bhaktivedanta Manor]], [[Watford]], England]]\nHindu tradition reveres Sita. She has been portrayed as an ideal daughter, an ideal wife and an ideal mother in various texts, stories, illustrations, movies,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dhar|first=Aarttee Kaul|title=Ramayana and Sita in Films and Popular Media:The Repositioning of a Globalised Version|url=https://www.academia.edu/11877534/Ramayana_and_Sita_in_Films_and_Popular_Media_The_Repositioning_of_a_Globalised_Version|language=en}}</ref> and modern media. Sita is often worshipped with Rama as his consort. The occasion of her marriage to Rama is celebrated as [[Vivaha Panchami]].\n\nThe actions, reactions, and instincts manifested by Sita at every juncture in a long and arduous life are deemed exemplary. Her story has been portrayed in the book [[Sitayanam]].<ref>[http://www.sitayanam.com \"Sitayanam \u2013 A Woman's Journey of Strength\" by Anju P. Bhargava]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101221413/http://www.sitayanam.com/ |date=1 January 2009 }}</ref> The values that she enshrined and adhered to at every point in the course of a demanding life are the values of womanly virtue held sacred by countless generations of Indians.\n\n==Temples==\nAlthough Sita's statue is always kept with Rama's statue in Rama temples, there are some temples dedicated to Sita:\n* [[Janaki Mandir]], located at [[Janakpur]], Nepal\n* [[Sita M\u0101\u012b Temple|Sita Mai Temple]], situated in Sitamai village in the Karnal district of Haryana, India\n* [[Sita Kund]], Punaura Dham, situated in Sitamarhi District in Bihar, India\n* [[Seetha Devi Temple]], Pulpally in the Wayanad district, Kerala, India\n* [[Seetha Amman Temple]], N\u00e4he [[Nuwara Eliya]], Sri Lanka\n* [[Sita temple]],  Phalswari, [[Pauri]] district, Uttarakhand (Proposed)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Kautilya |title=Uttarakhand set to come up with a massive Sita temple |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/uttarakhand-set-to-come-up-with-a-massive-sita-temple/articleshow/72012205.cms |accessdate=13 November 2019 |agency=The Times of India |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nJanki Mandir.JPG|[[Janaki Mandir]] of [[Janakpur]], [[Nepal]] is a center of pilgrimage where the wedding of Sri Rama and Sita took place and is re-enacted yearly as [[Vivaha Panchami]].\nLK-seetha-amman-kovil-01.jpg|Seetha Amman Kovil, N\u00e4he Nuwara Eliya, Sri Lanka.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Religion}}\n* [[Amba (Mahabharata)|Amba]]\n* [[Seetha kalyanam]]\n* [[Sita Sings the Blues]]\n*[[Siya Ke Ram]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Jain\n|first=Pannalal\n|title=Ravishenacharya's Padmapurana\n|year=2000\n|publisher=Bhartiya Jnanpith\n|location=New Delhi\n|isbn=978-81-263-0508-7\n|edition=8th\n|editor=Hiralal Jain, A.N. Upadhaye\n|language=Hindi\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Iyengar\n|first=Kodaganallur Ramaswami Srinivasa\n|title=Asian Variations In Ramayana\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CU92nFk5fU4C&pg=PA80\n|year=2005\n|publisher=Sahitya Akademi\n|isbn=978-81-260-1809-3\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Das\n|first=Sisir Kumar\n|title=A History of Indian Literature, 500-1399: From the Courtly to the Popular\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC3l1AbPM8sC&pg=PA124\n|year=2005\n|publisher=Sahitya Akademi\n|isbn=978-81-260-2171-0\n|page=124\n|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sita}}\n* [http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20111011015118/http://ancientindians.wordpress.com/sita-devi/ Sita Kalyanam in the Valmiki Ramayana]\n* {{Cite NIE|wstitle=S\u012bt\u0101|short=x}}\n\n{{Ramayana}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Hindudharma}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu goddesses]]\n[[Category:Mother goddesses]]\n[[Category:Ikshvaku dynasty]]\n[[Category:Mithila]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped people]]\n[[Category:Lakshmi]]\n[[Category:Characters in the Ramayana]]\n[[Category:Consorts of Vishnu]]\n[[Category:Hindu given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox deity\n| type = Hindu\n| image = File:Sitas Exile by Raja Ravi Varma (1848 - 1906).jpg\n| caption = Sita in exile by [[Raja Ravi Varma]].\n| name = Sita\n| Devanagari = \u0938\u0940\u0924\u093e\n| Sanskrit_transliteration = S\u012bt\u0101\n| affiliation = [[Avatar]] of [[Lakshmi]], [[Devi]], [[Panchakanya]]\n|dynasty =[[Kingdom of the Videhas|Videha]] ''(by birth)''<br />[[Raghuvanshi]]-[[Ikshvaku dynasty|Ikshvaku]]-[[Suryavansha|Suryavanshi]] ''(by marriage)''\n| consort = [[Rama]]\n| children = [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lava]] (son) <br /> [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] (son)\n| father = [[Janaka]]\n| mother= Sunaina\n| siblings = [[Urmila]] (sister)<br> [[Mandavi]] <br> [[Shrutakirti]] (cousins)\n| texts = ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]\n| festivals = Sita Navami, Janaki Jayanti, [[Vivaha Panchami]], [[Diwali]], [[Dussehra]]\n| birth_place = [[Mithila (region)|Mithila]]{{efn|Either present-day [[Sitamarhi district]], [[Bihar]], [[India]] <ref>https://m.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/rs-48-5-crore-for-sita-s-birthplace/cid/1440819</ref><ref name=\"telegraphindia.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/bihar/hot-spring-hot-spot-fair-begins-on-magh-full-moon-s-day/cid/1544104|title=Hot spring hot spot - Fair begins on Magh full moon's day|website=www.telegraphindia.com|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Sitamarhi\">{{cite encyclopedia | url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/546790/Sitamarhi | title=Sitamarhi | encyclopedia=Britannica | accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Sitamarhi\">{{cite web | url=http://sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/profile/index.htm | title=History of Sitamarhi | publisher=Official site of Sitamarhi district | accessdate=30 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220171523/http://sitamarhi.bih.nic.in/profile/index.htm | archive-date=20 December 2014 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> or Present-day [[Janakpur]], [[Province No. 2]], [[Nepal]]<ref>http://sacredsites.com/asia/nepal/janakpur.html</ref>}}}}\n{{Vaishnavism}}\n\n'''Sita''' is the central female character and one of the central figures in the Hindu epic,  ''[[Ramayana]]'' and [[Versions of Ramayana|its other versions]]. She is described as the daughter of the earth goddess, [[Bh\u016bmi]] or [[Prithvi]] and the adopted daughter of King [[Janaka]] of [[Videha]] and his wife, Queen Sunaina. She has a younger sister, [[Urmila]], and the female cousins [[Mandavi]] and [[Shrutakirti]].<ref name=\"Sutherland AOS\">{{cite web|last=Sutherland|first=Sally J.|title=Sita and Draupadi, Aggressive Behavior and Female Role-Models in the Sanskrit Epics|url=http://sseas.berkeley.edu/sites/default/files/faculty/files/sita_and_draupadi.pdf|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|accessdate=1 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Parmeshwaranand\">{{cite book|author=Swami Parmeshwaranand|title=Encyclopaedic Dictionaries of Puranas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FdIkaccgneAC&pg=PA1210|accessdate=31 July 2012|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-226-3|pages=1210\u20131220|date=2001-01-01}}</ref> Sita is known for her dedication, self-sacrifice, courage and purity.\n\nSita, in her youth, chooses Rama, the prince of [[Ayodhya]] as her husband in a swayamvara\u2014bride choosing the best from a crowd of suitors after a contest, where Rama proves his heroism and valor and martial power and \"defeats\" the other seekers for Seeta's hand in marriage. After the swayamvara,  she accompanies her husband to his kingdom, but later chooses to accompany her husband, along with her brother-in-law [[Lakshmana]], in his exile. While in exile, the trio settles in the [[Dandaka]] forest from where she is abducted by [[Ravana]], the [[Rakshasa]] king of [[Lanka]]. She is imprisoned in [[Ashoka Vatika]] in Lanka until she is rescued by Rama, who slays her captor. After the war, in some versions of the epic, Rama asks Sita to undergo Agni Pariksha (an [[Trial by ordeal#By fire|ordeal of fire]]) by which she proves her purity before she is accepted by Rama, which for the first time makes his brother Lakshmana get angry at him.\n\nIn some versions of the epic, the fire-god&nbsp;[[Agni]]&nbsp;creates [[Maya Sita]], who takes Sita's place and is abducted by Ravana and suffers his captivity, while the real Sita hides in the fire. During the Agni Pariksha, Maya Sita and the real Sita exchange places again. While some texts say that Maya Sita is destroyed in the flames of Agni Pariksha, others narrate how she is blessed and reborn as the epic heroine&nbsp;[[Draupadi]]&nbsp;or the goddess&nbsp;[[Alamelu|Padmavati]]. Some scriptures also mention her previous birth being&nbsp;[[Vedavati]], a woman Ravana tries to molest. {{citation needed|date=August 2017}} After proving her purity, Rama and Sita return to Ayodhya, where they are crowned as king and queen. After a few months, Sita becomes pregnant, to which a washerman makes insensitive comments on Sita to his wife, which Rama in disguise hears. Rama then sends Sita away on exile. Lakshmana is the one who leaves Sita in the forests near sage&nbsp;[[Valmiki]]'s ashram. Years later, Sita returns to the womb of her mother, the Earth, for release from a cruel world as a testimony of her purity after she reunites her two sons [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] and [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lava]] with their father Rama.<ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/78 78]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology and other names==\n[[File:Indischer Maler von 1780 001.jpg|thumb|Rama and Sita in the forest by an Indian painter from 1780]]\nThe goddess is best known by the name \"Sita\", derived from the Sanskrit word ''s\u012bta'', [[furrow]].<ref name=\"Chandra1998\">{{cite book|author=Suresh Chandra|title=Encyclopaedia of Hindu Gods and Goddesses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mfTE6kpz6XEC&pg=PA304|accessdate=1 August 2012|year=1998|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-039-9|pages=304\u2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Ramayana'', Janaka found her while ploughing as a part of a [[yagna]] and adopted her. The word ''S\u012bta'' was a poetic term, its imagery redolent of fecundity and the many blessings coming from settled agriculture. The Sita of the ''Ramayana'' may have been named after a more ancient [[Rigvedic deities|Vedic goddess]] Sita, who is mentioned once in the [[Rigveda]] as an earth goddess who blesses the land with good crops. In the [[Vedic period]], she was one of the goddesses associated with fertility. A Vedic hymn ([[s:The Rig Veda/Mandala 4/Hymn 57|Rig Veda 4:57]]) recites:\n{{cquote|''Auspicious Sita, come thou near;''\n''We venerate and worship thee'' <br />\n''That thou mayst bless and prosper us'' <br />\n''And bring us fruits abundantly.'' <br /> ''}}\n\nIn ''[[Harivamsa]]'', Sita is invoked as one of the names of the goddess Arya:\n{{cquote|''O goddess, you are the altar's center in the sacrifice,'' <br />\n''The priest's fee'' <br />\n''Sita to those who hold the plough'' <br />\n''And Earth to all living being. ''}}\n\nThe ''Kausik-sutra'' and the ''Paraskara-sutra'' associate her repeatedly as the wife of [[Parjanya]] (a god associated with rains) and [[Indra]].<ref name=\"Chandra1998\"/>\n\nSita is known by many epithets. She is called ''J\u0101naki'' as the daughter of Janaka and ''Maithili'' as the princess of Mithila.<ref name=Pauwels2007 /> As the wife of Rama, she is called ''Ram\u0101''. Her father Janaka had earned the sobriquet ''Videha'' due to his ability to transcend body consciousness; Sita is therefore also known as ''Vaidehi''.<ref name=\"Pauwels2007\">{{cite book|author=Heidi Rika Maria Pauwels|title=Indian Literature and Popular Cinema: Recasting Classics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LiXU4ihgMpgC&pg=PA53|accessdate=31 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-44741-6|pages=53\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDevi Sita while playing with her sisters in childhood had unknowingly lifted the table over which the bow had been placed; this was something that no one in Mithila could do. This incident was however observed by Janaka and he decided to make it a backdrop for Swayamvara because he wanted a son-in-law who was as strong as his daughter.<ref>\"https://m.dailyhunt.in/news/india/english/wittyfeed+india-epaper-witty/12+mythological+facts+about+sita+that+most+of+us+don+t+know-newsid-72197999\"</ref>\n\n==Legend==\n\n===Birth===\n[[File:Rama, Sita, Lakshmana.jpg|thumb|left|Rama, Sita and Lakshmana]]\nThe birthplace of Sita is disputed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biharlokmanch.org/indian_festivals_culture_aid_24.html|title=Bihar times|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019153403/http://www.biharlokmanch.org/indian_festivals_culture_aid_24.html|archivedate=19 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Sita Kund]]<ref name=\"telegraphindia.com\"/> pilgrimage site which is located in present-day [[Sitamarhi district]],<ref name=\"Sitamarhi\"/><ref name=\"History of Sitamarhi\"/>[[Bihar]], [[India]] is viewed as the birthplace of Sita. Apart from Sitamarhi, [[Janakpur]] which is located in the present-day [[Province No. 2]], [[Nepal]],<ref name=\"m.timesofindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/india/Modis-visit-to-Sitas-birthplace-in-Nepal-cancelled/articleshow/45220742.cms|title=Narendra Modi Cancells his visit to Sita's birthplace Janakpur, Nepal}}</ref><ref name=\"sacredsites.com\">{{cite web|url=http://sacredsites.com/asia/nepal/janakpur.html|title= Birthplace of Sita in Janakpur, Asia Travels}}</ref> is also described as Sita's birthplace.\n* ''Valmiki's Ramayana'': In Valmiki's Ramayana and its Tamil version Kamban's Ramavataram, Sita is said to have been discovered in a furrow in a ploughed field, believed to be [[Sitamarhi]] in [[Mithila (region)|Mithila region]] of present-day [[Bihar]], and for that reason is regarded as a daughter of [[Bh\u016bmi]] Devi<ref>{{cite web|title=The Story of Mother Sita the consort of Rama|url=http://www.salagram.net/parishad131.html|publisher=Salagram.net|accessdate=18 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530135807/http://salagram.net/parishad131.html|archivedate=30 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> (the goddess earth). She was discovered, adopted and brought up by [[Janaka]], king of [[History of Mithila|Mithila]] and his wife Sunaina.\n* ''Ramayana Manjari'': In ''Ramayana Manjari'' (verses 344\u2013366), North-western and Bengal recensions of Valmiki Ramayana, it has been described as on hearing a voice from the sky and then seeing [[Menaka]], Janaka expresses his wish to obtain a child, and when he finds the child, he hears the same voice again telling him the infant is his Spiritual child, born of Menaka.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n* ''Janka's real daughter'': In ''Ramopkhyana'' of the [[Mahabharata]] and also in ''Paumachariya'' of Vimala Suri, Sita has been depicted as Janaka's real daughter. According to Rev. Fr. [[Camille Bulcke]], this motif that Sita was the real daughter of Janaka, as described in ''Ramopkhyana Mahabharata'' was based on the authentic version of ''Valmiki Ramayana.'' Later, the story of Sita miraculously appearing in a furrow was inserted in ''Valmiki Ramayana''.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n* ''Reincarnation of [[Vedavati]]'': Some versions of the ''Ramayana'' suggest that Sita was a reincarnation of Vedavati. [[Ravana]] tried to molest Vedavati and her chastity was sullied beyond Ravana's redemption when she was performing penance to become the consort of Vishnu. Vedavati immolated herself on a pyre to escape Ravana's lust, vowing to return in another age and be the cause of Ravana's destruction. She was duly reborn as Sita.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n* ''Reincarnation of Manivati'': According to Gunabhadra's [[Uttara Purana]] of the ninth century BCE, Ravana disturbs the asceticism of Manivati, daughter of Amitavega of Alkapuri, and she pledges to take revenge on Ravana. Manivati is later reborn as the daughter of Ravana and [[Mandodari]]. But astrologers predicted the ruin of Ravana because of this child. So, Ravana orders to kill the child. Manivati is placed in a casket and buried in the ground of Mithila, where she is discovered by some of the farmers of the kingdom. Then Janaka, king of that state, adopts her.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\">{{cite journal|last=Singaravelu|first=S|title=S\u012bt\u0101's Birth and Parentage in the R\u0101ma Story|journal=Asian Folklore Studies|volume=41|issue=2|publisher=[[University of Malaya]], Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia|pages=235\u2013240|jstor=1178126|year=1982|doi=10.2307/1178126}}</ref>\n* ''Ravana's daughter'': In [[Rama in Jainism#Sanghadasa's version|Sanghadasa's Jaina version]] of Ramayana, and also in [[Adbhuta Ramayana]], Sita, entitled ''Vasudevahindi'', is born as the daughter of Ravana. According to this version, astrologers predict that first child of Vidyadhara Maya (Ravana's wife) will destroy his lineage. Thus, Ravana abandons her and orders the infant to be buried in a distant land where she is later discovered and adopted by Janaka.<ref name=\"Singaravelu 235\" />\n\n===Marriage===\n[[File:Rama breaking the bow to win Sita as wife.jpg|thumb|Rama breaks the bow to win Sita as wife.]]\nWhen Sita reaches adulthood, [[Janaka]] organizes a [[Swayamvara]] in [[Janakpurdham]] with the condition that Sita would marry only that person who would be able to string ''Pinaka'', the bow of the god [[Shiva]]. Janaka knew that the bow of Shiva was not even liftable, let alone stringable for ordinary mortals, and for selfish people it was not even approachable. Thus, Janaka tries to find the best husband for Sita.\n\nAt this time, [[Vishvamitra]] had brought Rama and his brother Lakshmana to the forest for the protection of sacrifice. Hearing about this ''swayamvara'', Vishvamitra asks Rama to participate in it and takes Rama and Lakshmana to the palace of Janaka in [[Janakpur]]. Janaka is greatly pleased to learn that Rama and Lakshmana are sons of Dasharatha. Next morning, in the middle of the hall, Rama lifts up the bow of Shiva with his left hand, fastens the string taut and breaks the bow in the process. However, another avatar of Vishnu, [[Parashurama]], became really angry as the bow of Shiva was broken. However, he does not realize that Rama is also an avatar of Vishnu, therefore after being informed of this, he apologizes for getting angry. Thus, Rama fulfills Janaka's condition to marry Sita. Later on [[Vivaha Panchami]], a marriage ceremony is conducted under the guidance of Satananda. Rama marries Sita, Bharata marries Mandavi, Lakshmana marries Urmila and Shatrughna marries Shrutakirti.<ref name=Parmeshwaranand />\n\n===Exile and abduction===\n[[File:Ravi Varma-Ravana Sita Jathayu.jpg|thumb|upright|Ravana cuts off Jatayu's wing while abducting Sita]]\nSome time after the wedding, [[Kaikeyi]], Rama's stepmother, compelled Dasharatha to make Bharata king, prompted by the coaxing of her maid [[Manthara]], and forced Rama to leave Ayodhya and spend a period of exile in the forests of [[Dandaka]] and later Panchavati. Sita and Lakshmana willingly renounced the comforts of the palace and joined Rama in exile. The Panchavati forest became the scene for Sita's abduction by Ravana, King of Lanka. Ravana kidnapped Sita, disguising himself as a mendicant, while Rama was away fetching a [[Maricha|golden deer]] to please her. Some versions of the ''Ramayana'' describe Sita taking refuge with the fire-god [[Agni]], while [[Maya Sita]], her illusionary double, is kidnapped by the demon-king. [[Jatayu (Ramayana)|Jatayu]], the vulture-king, tried to protect Sita but Ravana chopped off his wings. Jatayu survived long enough to inform Rama of what had happened.<ref name=\"Mani720\">Mani pp. 720-3; {{cite book | last = Mani | first = Vettam | title = Puranic Encyclopaedia: a Comprehensive Dictionary with Special Reference to the Epic and Puranic Literature | url = https://archive.org/details/puranicencyclopa00maniuoft | publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publishers | year = 1975 <!-- | location = Delhi --> | isbn = 978-0-8426-0822-0 | authorlink = Vettam Mani }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hanuman Encounters Sita in Ashokavana.jpg|thumb|left|Hanuman finds Sita in Ashokavana]]\nRavana took her back to his kingdom in Lanka and Sita was held as a prisoner in one of his palaces. During her captivity for a year in Lanka, Ravana expressed his desire for her; however, Sita refused his advances and struggled to maintain her chastity. [[Hanuman]] was sent by Rama to seek Sita and eventually succeeded in discovering Sita's whereabouts. Sita gave Hanuman her jewellery and asked him to give it to her husband. Hanuman returned across the sea to Rama.<ref name=\"Mani720\"/>\n\nSita was finally rescued by Rama, who waged a war to defeat Ravana. Upon rescue, Rama makes Sita undergo a trial by fire to prove her chastity. In some versions of ''Ramayana'', during this test the fire-god Agni appears in front of Rama and attests to Sita's purity, or hands over to him the real Sita and declares it was Maya Sita who was abducted by Ravana.<ref name=\"Mani720\"/> The Thai version of the Ramayana, however, tells of Sita walking on the fire, of her own accord, to feel clean, as opposed to jumping in it. She is not burnt, and the coals turn to lotuses.After proving that Sita is still pure, she returns to Ayodhya. But the citizens of Ayodhaya don't accept Sita and says that she is impure, and ram has to forcefully sent Sita against his wish. After 12 yrs he go backs to Sita and asks her to come back to Ayodhya. But Sita denies and says bhumi to take her inside herself.. Sita goes inside the earth and gives her sons to Rama....\n\n=The life of Sita, after exiling again and the reason of exiling according to mythology=\nThe couple came back to Ayodhya, where Rama was crowned king with Sita by his side.\n\nWhile Rama's trust and affection for Sita never wavered, it soon became evident that some people in Ayodhya could not accept Sita's long captivity under Ravana. During Rama's period of rule, an intemperate [[Dhobi|washerman]], while berating his wayward wife, declared that he was \"no pusillanimous Rama who would take his wife back after she had lived in the house of another man\". This statement was reported back to Rama, who knew that the accusation against Sita was baseless. Nevertheless, he would not let [[slander]] undermine his rule, so he sent Sita away.\n\nThus Sita was forced into exile a second time. Sita, who was pregnant, was given refuge in the hermitage of [[Valmiki]], where she delivered twin sons named [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]] and [[Lava (Ramayana)|Lava]].<ref name=Parmeshwaranand /> In the hermitage, Sita raised her sons alone, as a single mother.<ref name=\"Contemporary Influence of Sita by\">{{cite web|last=Bhargava|first=Anju P.|title=Contemporary Influence of Sita by|url=http://www.infinityfoundation.com/ECITsitaframeset.htm|publisher=The Infinity Foundation|accessdate=31 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713001426/http://www.infinityfoundation.com/ECITsitaframeset.htm|archivedate=13 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> They grew up to be valiant and intelligent and were eventually united with their father. Once she had witnessed the acceptance of her children by Rama, Sita sought final refuge in the arms of her mother [[Bh\u016bmi]]. Hearing her plea for release from an unjust world and from a life that had rarely been happy, the Earth dramatically split open; Bh\u016bmi appeared and took Sita away.(Abounding of Devi S\u012bta appears in Uttara K\u0101nda which is considered by some people as later added kanda).\n\nSita's exile during her pregnancy was because of a curse during her childhood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vedpuran.files.wordpress.com/2011/10/padam-puran.pdf|title=Padma-puran pdf file|date=1 October 2018|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref> According to [[Padma Purana|Padma-puran]], Sita had caught a pair of divine parrots which were from Valmiki's ashram when she was young. The birds were talking about story of Sri Ram heard in [[Valmiki]] ashram which intrigued Sita. She has the ability to talk with animals. The female bird was pregnant at that time. She requested Sita to let them go and return from Valmiki's Ashram as they knew only up to their marriage but Sita only allowed her male companion to fly away but female parrot died because of separation from her companion. As a result, the male bird cursed Sita that she would suffer a similar fate of being separated from her husband during pregnancy. The male bird was reborn as the washerman.\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nSita test fires.png|Sita's fire test\nSita Bhum Pravesh.jpg|Sita returns to her mother, the Earth, as Sri Rama, her sons, and the sages watch in astonishment.\nRama and sita in pavilion.jpg|Rama and Sita from Uttara-Kanda.\n</gallery>\n\n==Speeches in the ''Ramayana''==\n[[File:Ramayana - Marriage of Rama Bharata Lakshmana and Shatrughna.jpg|thumb|250px|The marriage of the four sons of Dasharatha with the four daughters of Siradhvaja and Kushadhvaja Janakas. Rama and Sita, Lakshmana and Urmila, Bharata and Mandavi and Shatrughna with Shrutakirti.]]\nWhile the ''Ramayana'' mostly concentrates on Rama's actions, Sita also speaks many times during the exile. The first time is in the town of [[Chitrakoot Dham (Karwi)|Chitrakuta]] where she narrates an ancient story to Rama, whereby Rama promises to Sita that he will never kill anybody without provocation.\n\nThe second time Sita is shown talking prominently is when she speaks to Ravana. Ravana has come to her in the form of a mendicant and Sita tells him that he does not look like one.\n\nSome of her most prominent speeches are with Hanuman when he reaches Lanka. Hanuman wants an immediate union of Rama and Sita and thus he proposes to Sita to ride on his back. Sita refuses as she does not want to run away like a thief; instead she wants her husband Rama to come and defeat Ravana to save her.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Valmiki |first1=Ramayana |title=Sundarkanda, sarga 37 |url=https://www.valmiki.iitk.ac.in/sloka?field_kanda_tid=5&language=dv&field_sarga_value=37 |website=www.valmiki.iitk.ac.in |publisher=IIT Kanpur}}</ref>\n\n==Jain version==\n{{main|Rama in Jainism}}\n[[File:Hanuman before Rama.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Rama seated with Sita, fanned by [[Lakshmana]], while [[Hanuman]] pays his respects]]\nSita is said to be the daughter of [[Ravana]]'s queen [[Mandodari]]. It was predicted that the first child of Mandodari would bring annihilation to the family. Hence, Ravana deserted the child when she was born. The minister who was responsible for this took her in a pearl-box, placed her near a plough and told King [[Janaka]] of [[Mithila (ancient)|Mithila]] that the girl had been born from the furrow. Janaka's queen Sunaina became Sita's foster mother.\n\nThere is also a narration about Sita's brother Bhamandala. He did not know that Sita was his sister and wanted to marry her. He even wanted to abduct her. This story ends when Bhamandala, after learning that Sita is his sister, becomes a [[Jain monasticism|Jain ascetic]].\n\n==Symbolism==\n{{unreferenced section|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Hermitage of Valmiki, Folio from the \"Nadaun\" Ramayana (Adventures of Rama) LACMA AC1999.127.45.jpg|thumb|250px|Sita in the [[hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]] of Valmiki]]\nA female deity of agricultural fertility by the name Sita was known before Valmiki's ''Ramayana'', but was overshadowed by better-known goddesses associated with fertility. According to ''Ramayana'', Sita was discovered in a furrow when Janaka was ploughing. Since Janaka was a king, it is likely that ploughing was part of a royal ritual to ensure fertility of the land. Sita is considered to be a child of Mother Earth, produced by union between the king and the land. Sita is a personification of Earth's fertility, abundance, and well-being.\n\n==Swami Vivekananda on Sita==\n[[File:Valmiki train Lava Kushas in Art of Archery.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Valmiki training Lava Kusha (sons of Rama & Sita) in the art of archery.]]\n[[Swami Vivekananda]] states that Rama is considered the type of the Absolute and Sita that of Power. Sita is the ideal of a woman in India and worshiped as God incarnate.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cwsv.belurmath.org/volume_9/lectures_and_discourses/the_women_of_india.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304225348/http://cwsv.belurmath.org/volume_9/lectures_and_discourses/the_women_of_india.htm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAccording to Swami Vivekananda, Sita is typical of India \u2013 the idealized India. Swami Vivekananda assured that if world literature of the past and world literature of the future were thoroughly exhausted, yet, it would not be possible to find another Sita, because Sita is unique; the character was depicted once for all. Swami Vivekananda felt there may have been several Ramas, perhaps, but never more than one Sita.\n\nVivekananda said:\n\n{{Quote|All our mythology may vanish, even our Vedas may depart and our Sanskrit language may vanish forever, but so long as there will be five Hindus living here, even if only seeking the most vulgar patois, there will be the story of Sita present.}}\n\nSita was a true Indian by nature, Vivekananda concluded, who never returned injury.<ref>The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda/Volume 4/Lectures and Discourses/The Ramayana</ref>\n\n==Portrayal==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2018}}\n[[File:Srisita ram laxman hanuman manor.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Deities Sita (far right), Rama (center), Lakshmana (far left) and Hanuman (below, seated) at [[Bhaktivedanta Manor]], [[Watford]], England]]\nHindu tradition reveres Sita. She has been portrayed as an ideal daughter, an ideal wife and an ideal mother in various texts, stories, illustrations, movies,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dhar|first=Aarttee Kaul|title=Ramayana and Sita in Films and Popular Media:The Repositioning of a Globalised Version|url=https://www.academia.edu/11877534/Ramayana_and_Sita_in_Films_and_Popular_Media_The_Repositioning_of_a_Globalised_Version|language=en}}</ref> and modern media. Sita is often worshipped with Rama as his consort. The occasion of her marriage to Rama is celebrated as [[Vivaha Panchami]].\n\nThe actions, reactions, and instincts manifested by Sita at every juncture in a long and arduous life are deemed exemplary. Her story has been portrayed in the book [[Sitayanam]].<ref>[http://www.sitayanam.com \"Sitayanam \u2013 A Woman's Journey of Strength\" by Anju P. Bhargava]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090101221413/http://www.sitayanam.com/ |date=1 January 2009 }}</ref> The values that she enshrined and adhered to at every point in the course of a demanding life are the values of womanly virtue held sacred by countless generations of Indians.\n\n==Temples==\nAlthough Sita's statue is always kept with Rama's statue in Rama temples, there are some temples dedicated to Sita:\n* [[Janaki Mandir]], located at [[Janakpur]], Nepal\n* [[Sita M\u0101\u012b Temple|Sita Mai Temple]], situated in Sitamai village in the Karnal district of Haryana, India\n* [[Sita Kund]], Punaura Dham, situated in Sitamarhi District in Bihar, India\n* [[Seetha Devi Temple]], Pulpally in the Wayanad district, Kerala, India\n* [[Seetha Amman Temple]], N\u00e4he [[Nuwara Eliya]], Sri Lanka\n* [[Sita temple]],  Phalswari, [[Pauri]] district, Uttarakhand (Proposed)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singh |first1=Kautilya |title=Uttarakhand set to come up with a massive Sita temple |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/dehradun/uttarakhand-set-to-come-up-with-a-massive-sita-temple/articleshow/72012205.cms |accessdate=13 November 2019 |agency=The Times of India |date=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nJanki Mandir.JPG|[[Janaki Mandir]] of [[Janakpur]], [[Nepal]] is a center of pilgrimage where the wedding of Sri Rama and Sita took place and is re-enacted yearly as [[Vivaha Panchami]].\nLK-seetha-amman-kovil-01.jpg|Seetha Amman Kovil, N\u00e4he Nuwara Eliya, Sri Lanka.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Religion}}\n* [[Amba (Mahabharata)|Amba]]\n* [[Seetha kalyanam]]\n* [[Sita Sings the Blues]]\n*[[Siya Ke Ram]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n|last=Jain\n|first=Pannalal\n|title=Ravishenacharya's Padmapurana\n|year=2000\n|publisher=Bhartiya Jnanpith\n|location=New Delhi\n|isbn=978-81-263-0508-7\n|edition=8th\n|editor=Hiralal Jain, A.N. Upadhaye\n|language=Hindi\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Iyengar\n|first=Kodaganallur Ramaswami Srinivasa\n|title=Asian Variations In Ramayana\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CU92nFk5fU4C&pg=PA80\n|year=2005\n|publisher=Sahitya Akademi\n|isbn=978-81-260-1809-3\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=Das\n|first=Sisir Kumar\n|title=A History of Indian Literature, 500-1399: From the Courtly to the Popular\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC3l1AbPM8sC&pg=PA124\n|year=2005\n|publisher=Sahitya Akademi\n|isbn=978-81-260-2171-0\n|page=124\n|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Sita}}\n* [http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20111011015118/http://ancientindians.wordpress.com/sita-devi/ Sita Kalyanam in the Valmiki Ramayana]\n* {{Cite NIE|wstitle=S\u012bt\u0101|short=x}}\n\n{{Ramayana}}\n{{HinduMythology}}\n{{Hindudharma}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu goddesses]]\n[[Category:Mother goddesses]]\n[[Category:Ikshvaku dynasty]]\n[[Category:Mithila]]\n[[Category:Kidnapped people]]\n[[Category:Lakshmi]]\n[[Category:Characters in the Ramayana]]\n[[Category:Consorts of Vishnu]]\n[[Category:Hindu given names]]\n", "name_user": "2402:3a80:e6d:aeb0:1184:ef27:e87f:6f9e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sita"}
{"title_page": "Conus unifasciatus", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Conus unifasciatus\n| image =Conus unifasciatus 1.jpg\n| image2 =Conus unifasciatus 2.jpg\n| image_caption =Apertural and abapertural views of [[gastropod shell|shell]] of ''Conus unifasciatus''  <small>Kiener, L.C., 1845</small>\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| authority = Kiener, 1845\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n* ''Conus (Lautoconus) unifasciatus'' <small>Kiener, 1850</small> \u00b7 accepted, alternate representation\n* ''Lautoconus unifasciatus'' <small>(Kiener, 1850)</small>\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Conus unifasciatus''''' is a species of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Conidae]], the [[Conus|cone snails]] and their allies.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|224304|''Conus unifasciatus'' Kiener, 1845||27 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nLike all species within the genus ''Conus'', these snails are [[predatory]] and [[venomous]]. They are capable of \"stinging\" humans, therefore live ones should be handled carefully or not at all.\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 22&nbsp;mm and 37&nbsp;mm. The shell has the general form of [''[Californiconus californicus]]''. Its color is chocolate, with a rather broad yellowish brown band just below the shoulder.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualconch06tryorich G.W. Tryon (1884) Manual of Conchology, structural and systematic, with illustrations of the species, vol. VI; Philadelphia, Academy of Natural Sciences]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis species occurs in the Atlantic Ocean off [[West Africa]] and [[Senegal]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/88016 Kiener L.C. 1844\u20131850. Sp\u00e9cies g\u00e9n\u00e9ral et iconographie des coquilles vivantes. Vol. 2. Famille des Enroul\u00e9es. Genre Cone (Conus, Lam.), pp. 1\u2013379, pl. 1\u2013111 &#91;pp. 1\u201348 (1846); 49\u2013160 (1847); 161\u2013192 (1848); 193\u2013240 (1849); 241-&#91;379&#93;(assumed to be 1850); plates 4,6 (1844); 2\u20133, 5, 7\u201332, 34\u201336, 38, 40\u201350 (1845); 33, 37, 39, 51\u201352, 54\u201356, 57\u201368, 74\u201377 (1846); 1, 69\u201373, 78\u2013103 (1847); 104\u2013106 (1848); 107 (1849); 108\u2013111 (1850)&#93;. Paris, Rousseau & J.B. Bailli\u00e8re]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://biology.burke.washington.edu/conus/catalogue/index.php The ''Conus'' Biodiversity website]\n* [http://www.coneshells-am.ru/ Cone Shells \u2013 Knights of the Sea]\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=8|id=7848|title=''Lautoconus unifasciatus''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1608670}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conus Unifasciatus}}\n[[Category:Conus|unifasciatus]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1845]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Conus unifasciatus\n| image =Conus unifasciatus 1.jpg\n| image2 =Conus unifasciatus 2.jpg\n| image_caption =Apertural and abapertural views of [[gastropod shell|shell]] of ''Conus unifasciatus''  <small>Kiener, L.C., 1845</small>\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| authority = Kiener, 1845\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n* ''Conus (Lautoconus) unifasciatus'' <small>Kiener, 1850</small> \u00b7 accepted, alternate representation\n* ''Lautoconus unifasciatus'' <small>(Kiener, 1850)</small>\n| display_parents = 3\n}}\n\n'''''Conus unifasciatus''''' is a species of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Conidae]], the [[Conus|cone snails]] and their allies.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|224304|''Conus unifasciatus'' Kiener, 1845||27 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nLike all species within the genus ''Conus'', these snails are [[predatory]] and [[venomous]]. They are capable of \"stinging\" humans, therefore live ones should be handled carefully or not at all.\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 22&nbsp;mm and 37&nbsp;mm. The shell has the general form of [''[Californiconus californicus]]''. Its color is chocolate, with a rather broad yellowish brown band just below the shoulder.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualconch06tryorich G.W. Tryon (1884) Manual of Conchology, structural and systematic, with illustrations of the species, vol. VI; Philadelphia, Academy of Natural Sciences]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis species occurs in the Atlantic Ocean off [[West Africa]] and [[Senegal]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/88016 Kiener L.C. 1844\u20131850. Sp\u00e9cies g\u00e9n\u00e9ral et iconographie des coquilles vivantes. Vol. 2. Famille des Enroul\u00e9es. Genre Cone (Conus, Lam.), pp. 1\u2013379, pl. 1\u2013111 &#91;pp. 1\u201348 (1846); 49-160 (1847); 161-192 (1848); 193-240 (1849); 241-&#91;379&#93;(assumed to be 1850); plates 4,6 (1844); 2\u20133, 5, 7\u201332, 34\u201336, 38, 40-50 (1845); 33, 37, 39, 51\u201352, 54\u201356, 57\u201368, 74-77 (1846); 1, 69\u201373, 78-103 (1847); 104-106 (1848); 107 (1849); 108-111 (1850)&#93;. Paris, Rousseau & J.B. Bailli\u00e8re]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://biology.burke.washington.edu/conus/catalogue/index.php The ''Conus'' Biodiversity website]\n* [http://www.coneshells-am.ru/ Cone Shells \u2013 Knights of the Sea]\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=8|id=7848|title=''Lautoconus unifasciatus''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1608670}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conus Unifasciatus}}\n[[Category:Conus|unifasciatus]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1845]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conus_unifasciatus"}
{"title_page": "Alan Winde", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Alan Winde\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image               = Alan Winde.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Winde in 2018\n| office              = 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]\n| status              = \n| premier             = \n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Helen Zille]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]\n| premier1            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1         = 1 November 2018\n| term_end1           = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Dan Plato]]\n| successor1          = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office2             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]\n| premier2            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2         = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2           = 1 November 2018\n| alongside2          = \n| constituency2       = \n| predecessor2        = ''Position established''\n| successor2          = [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] \n| majority2           = \n| prior_term2         =\n| office3             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]\n| premier3            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2009\n| term_end3           = 26 May 2014\n| alongside3          = \n| constituency3       = \n| predecessor3        = Garth Strachan\n| successor3          = ''Position dissolved''\n| majority3           = \n| prior_term3         =\n| office4            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start4        = 15 June 1999\n| birthname          = Alan Richard Winde\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knysna]], [[Cape Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = [[South Africa]]n\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (1999\u20132000) <br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (Before 1999)\n| spouse             = Tracy Winde (m. 1993)\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = [[Knysna]]<br />[[Cape Town]]\n| education          = Knysna High School\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician<br />Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Alan Richard Winde''' (born 18 March 1965) is a South African politician and previous businessman.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', Western Cape, 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 30 September 2018.</ref> He is currently serving as the 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]] since his election in 2019, and a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since 1999. He previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]], the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]] and the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]. Winde is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).\n\nBorn in [[Knysna]], Winde attended Knysna High School. He has experience as a businessman and entrepreneur since he established several businesses. He also worked for and managed numerous companies. He started his political career as a municipal and district councillor in the early 1990s. Shortly afterwards in 1999, he was elected to the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He has held various leadership positions in the Democratic Alliance provincial parliament caucus. Winde was appointed [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]] in May 2009 and served until May 2014, when he assumed the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet], ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref><ref>Williams, Murray. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Democratic Alliance selected Winde to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-named-da-candidate-to-take-over-from-helen-zille-as-premier/ Alan Winde named DA candidate to take over from Helen Zille as premier], ''TimesLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref> In October 2018, Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Winde to the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]. He took office on 1 November 2018.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the Democratic Alliance retained their majority in the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]], but with a decrease in the number of seats.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-10-democratic-alliance-officially-wins-the-western-cape-vote/ It's official: The Democratic Alliance has won the Western Cape], ''TimesLIVE'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> Winde was elected Premier on 22 May 2019 and succeeded Helen Zille. He is the second Western Cape Premier from the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Roux |first1=Nckey |title=Winde formally elected as Premier on 22 May |url=https://www.georgeherald.com/News/Article/Elections-2019/premier-elect-inaugurated-on-22-may-201905131129 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=George Herald |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and business career==\n===Family and personal life===\nWinde was born on 18 March 1965 in the town of [[Knysna]]. He attended and matriculated from Knysna High School. He married Tracy Winde in 1993. They have two children named Lauren and Jason.<ref name = \"onesaforall\">[https://www.onesouthafricaforall.co.za/ Alan Winde], ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde's father, William Dave Winde, died on 1 August 2019.<ref>(In Afrikaans) [https://www.son.co.za/Nuus/Suid-Kaap/premier-se-pa-oorlede-20190801 Winde se pa oorlede], ''Son Digitaal'', 1 August 2019. Retrieved on 1 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===Business career===\nWinde has experience as an entrepreneur. He established and managed many small businesses. He was also a director of a tour company and a business broker with Aldes Business Brokers.<ref name=\"onesaforall\" />\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Minister Alan Winde (cropped).jpg|x200px|thumb|left|Winde as Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism in 2013]]\nWinde ran as an independent candidate and was elected to the South Cape District Council in 1996. He had previously served as a councillor for the Outeniqua Rural Council. Shortly after being elected a district councillor, the [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] recruited him to be a candidate for the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He was elected in the [[1999 South African general election|general election of 1999]].<ref name =\"bizzabo\">[https://events.bizzabo.com/u-start-conference-africa/agenda/speakers/89264 Alan Winde - Bizzabo], ''U-Start Conference Africa''. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe took office as a Member on 15 June 2009. During his first term, he served as Western Cape Provincial Finance Chairman and a Member of the Executive Committee. He returned to the Provincial Parliament following the 2004 general election. Briefly, before being re-elected in 2009, he served as Chief Whip of the Official Opposition, Party Spokesperson on Environment and Planning and Deputy Party Spokesperson on Economic Development and Tourism.<ref name=\"bizzabo\" />\n\nPremier Helen Zille appointed Winde to the position of Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism following his re-election in May 2009. Constitutional Court Judge [[Yvonne Mokgoro]] swore him in as Provincial Minister on 7 May 2009. He consequently succeeded Garth Strachan.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/appointment-western-cape-provincial-cabinet Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 7 May 2009. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the 2014 elections, Premier Helen Zille announced that Winde would now hold the title of Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities and only lead the Provincial Departments of Agriculture, Economic Development and Tourism. The Provincial Finance Department would be an independent department with its own Provincial Minister. Western Cape Deputy Judge President Jeanette Traverso swore him in on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Winde was selected by the DA's Federal Executive to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate for the 2019 provincial election.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-da-names-alan-winde-western-cape-premier-candidate WATCH: DA names Alan Winde as Western Cape Premier candidate], ''eNCA'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPremier Helen Zille announced in October 2018 that Winde would move to the Provincial Community Safety Department as incumbent Provincial Minister [[Dan Plato]] had announced his intention to resign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thaw |first1=Regan |title=Alan Winde to take over WC Community Safety portfolio |url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=19 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |archivedate=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alan Winde replacing Dan Plato as community safety MEC |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/alan-winde-replacing-dan-plato-as-community-safety-mec-17553379 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> Winde was succeeded by [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] on 1 November 2018. He subsequently assumed the post of Provincial Minister of Community Safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Economic Development on swearing in of MEC Beverley Sch\u00e4fer |url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/western-cape-economic-development-swearing-mec-beverley-sch%C3%A4fer-1-nov-2018-0000 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=South African Government |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nWinde has served as acting Premier of the Western Cape on various brief occasions.<ref>[https://twitter.com/alanwinde/status/1092696090162446337 Alan Winde on Twitter: \"I have just been sworn in as Acting Premier. I agreed with the Judge not to invade any neighboring country.\"]. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He represented the provincial government at the [[State of the Nation Address (South Africa)|February 2019 State of the Nation Address]], as [[Helen Zille]] was in [[Germany]].<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sona-2019-from-thuma-mina-to-new-dawn-fades-as-bosasa-casts-a-shadow-20190208 SONA 2019: From 'Thuma Mina' to 'New Dawn Fades' as Bosasa casts a shadow], News24, 8 February 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n== Premier of the Western Cape (2019\u2013present)==\n===Campaign===\n{{see also|2019 Western Cape provincial election}}\n[[File:Alan Winde For Premier Campaign Bus 2019 (cropped).jpg|270px|thumb|Alan Winde for Premier campaign bus, which was unveiled in April 2019.]]\nWinde emerged as the front-runner quite early on in the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=Who wants to be the Western Cape's next |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/who-wants-to-be-the-western-capes-next-premier-15527764 |accessdate=28 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, Democratic Alliance Federal Leader, [[Mmusi Maimane]], announced Winde as the party's Western Cape Premier candidate to succeed Premier [[Helen Zille]] after the 2019 elections. Winde defeated prominent candidates such as the Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]], and Member of Parliament [[David Maynier]]. After the announcement, Madikizela endorsed Winde and offered his full support to Winde's campaign.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', [[Western Cape]], 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Dentlinger, Lindsay. [https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/featured/da-wc-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-backs-alan-winde-as-premier-candidate/ar-BBNA1TB DA WC leader Bonginkosi Madikizela backs Alan Winde as premier candidate], ''MSN'', 20 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance launched their campaign to retain the Western Cape after the 2019 elections at the [[Cape Town Stadium]] on 29 September 2018. At the event, Mmusi Maimane highlighted the party's achievements while governing the province, such as the province's low unemployment rate and that the party had turned the previously struggling Provincial Education Department into one of the best functioning departments in South Africa.<ref>Isaacs, Lauren. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/30/da-determined-to-retain-western-cape-in-2019-elections DA determined to retain Western Cape in 2019 elections],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/unity-the-rallying-call-for-western-cape-da-as-it-launches-its-election-campaign-20180929 Unity the rallying call for Western Cape DA, as it launches its election campaign], ''News24'', 29 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter he was announced as the premier candidate, Winde embarked on a listening tour and travelled to various communities in the [[Western Cape]].<ref>[https://pr.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-DA-Western-Cape-Premier-Candidate-Winde-takes-Listening-Tour-to-George-8001073 #WindeForPremier: DA Western Cape Premier Candidate Winde takes Listening Tour to George], ''African News Agency'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nHe also campaigned for local DA candidates in by-elections. For instance, he went to the community of De Doorns to campaign for a DA candidate in a hotly-contested by-election. The DA candidate, Luwellyn Willemse, retained ward 3 of the [[Breede Valley Local Municipality|Breede Valley municipality]] by earning a total of 1,101 votes (52.16%).<ref>{{cite news |title=DA retains ward in Breede Valley municipal by-election |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2027939/da-retains-ward-in-breede-valley-municipal-by-election/ |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-Alan-Winde-to-address-supporters-at-De-Doorns-final-rally-ahead-of-by-election-7777913 #WindeForPremier: Alan Winde to address supporters at De Doorns final rally ahead of by-election], ''African News Agency''. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde launched the Democratic Alliance's 2019 provincial voter registration campaign on 4 January 2019. Winde and other Democratic Alliance members erected party registration posters in [[Mitchells Plain]], ahead of the Independent Electoral Commission's registration weekend on 26 and 27 January 2019.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-winde-launches-das-campaign-voter-registration-plan-criticised-18686993 WATCH: Winde launches DA's campaign, voter registration plan criticised], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 5 August 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance held its provincial Plan of Action Rally on 2 March 2019 at the [[Bellville Velodrome]] and launched their provincial party manifesto. Winde and various other DA politicians addressed thousands of party supporters. Winde assured that he would take on the national government for the Western Cape to receive its own, decentralised [[Rail transport in South Africa|rail]] and [[South African Police Service|police service]]. He pledged to increase the availability of [[Housing voucher|housing vouchers]] and vowed to spend [[Taxation in South Africa|tax money]] properly.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/da-comes-out-guns-blazing-to-retain-control-of-wc DA comes out guns blazing to retain control of WC], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref><ref>Payne, Sune. [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-03-04-da-punts-control-of-rail-and-policing-in-western-cape-as-party-launches-provincial-manifesto/ DA punts control of rail and policing in Western Cape as party launches provincial manifesto], ''The Daily Maverick'', 4 March 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref><ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/maimane-unemployment-will-continue-to-rise-the-longer-anc-stays-in-power Maimane: Unemployment will continue to rise the longer ANC stays in power],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde vowed on 11 March 2019 to build a police station in the gang-riddled community of [[Bonteheuwel]] due to the large number of murders that occur in the suburb.<ref>Mortlock, Monique.  \n[https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/11/winde-promises-to-a-police-station-in-bonteheuwel-if-da-wins-elections Winde promises to build police station in Bonteheuwel if DA wins elections], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde participated in the first [[eNCA]] Town Hall Debate, hosted at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]] on 14 March 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-emotions-run-high-encas-town-hall-debate WATCH: Emotions run high at eNCA's Town Hall Debate], ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref> The debate included many senior Western Cape politicians, such as former African National Congress Premier [[Ebrahim Rasool]], Economic Freedom Fighters City of Cape Town councillor [[Melikhaya Xego]], Good Party Leader [[Patricia de Lille]], and Freedom Front Plus Western Cape Premier candidate [[Peter Marais]].<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/senior-politicians-trade-barbs-campaign-at-enca-townhall-debate-in-the-capes-mitchells-plain-20190314 Senior politicians trade barbs, campaign at eNCA townhall debate in the Cape's Mitchells Plain], ''News24'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/live-video-cape-town-pre-election-town-hall-meetings WATCH: eNCA Town Hall Debate - Cape Town], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019.  Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and [[Mmusi Maimane]] revealed the Democratic Alliance's alternative energy plan for the Western Cape on 27 March 2019, in which the province acquires electricity directly from Independent Power Producers (IPPs).<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-maimane-winde-reveal-das-alternative-energy-plan-20115500 WATCH: Maimane, Winde reveal DA's alternative energy plan], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 27 March 2019. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance retained control of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, but with a decrease in the number of seats, on 8 May 2019.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/elections/2128368/live-da-secures-majority-again-in-western-cape-election-results/ LIVE: DA secures majority again in Western Cape election results], ''The Citizen'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> The party celebrated their election win in the province on 16 May 2019.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/campaigning-a-reality-check-das-winde-admits-as-he-thanks-the-western-cape-20190516 Campaigning a 'reality check', DA's Winde admits as he thanks the Western Cape], ''News24'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved on 18 May 2019.</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWinde was elected Premier of the Western Cape on 22 May 2019 during the first sitting of the Sixth Provincial Parliament. He received 24 out of the 34 valid votes. Six ballots were spoilt, and there were two abstentions. His main challenger for the post was [[Cameron Dugmore]] of the [[African National Congress]], who received only 10 out of the 34 valid votes.<ref>Lee, Samantha. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/breaking-winde-sworn-in-as-western-cape-premier-20190522 Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''News24'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>Mortlock, Monique. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/da-s-winde-elected-as-new-wc-premier DA's Winde elected as new WC premier], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2133822/winde-elected-western-cape-premier/ Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''The Citizen'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde announced the formation of his Provincial Cabinet on 23 May 2019. He retained four ministers in their existing portfolios, while he moved three to other portfolios and appointed three new members. He appointed former DA Member of Parliament and premier candidate contender, [[David Maynier]], to the post of Provincial Minister of Finance and Economic Opportunities, while he moved [[Albert Fritz]] and [[Ivan Meyer]] to the posts of Provincial Minister of Community Safety and Provincial Minister of Agriculture, respectively. Winde also said that all the newly-appointed cabinet members would undergo lifestyle audits.<ref name=\"provincial cabinet\">\n*Sicetsha, Andile. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/western-cape-premier-alan-winde-new-cabinet/ Western Cape Premier Alan Winde announces new Cabinet], ''The South African'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 9 September 2019.\n*Meyer, Dan. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new], ''TimesLVE'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.\n*[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-names-western-cape-cabinet-20190523 Winde names new Western Cape cabinet], ''News24'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Nkanjeni, Unathi. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-24-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-western-cape-provincial-cabinet/ What you need to know about the Western Cape provincial cabinet], ''TimesLIVE'', 24 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.\n*Kiewit, Lester. [https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-23-windes-cabinet-to-undergo-lifestyle-audits Winde\u2019s cabinet to undergo lifestyle audits], ''Mail & Guardian'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde confirmed on 3 June 2019 that a provincial children's commissioner would be appointed before the end of 2019 or in early 2020. He added that the commissioner would have the authority to monitor, investigate, research, lobby and educate on issues, policy, services and legislation that affect children.<ref>Kahla, Cheryl. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/child-protection-week-western-cape-to-childrens-commissioner-2019/ Child Protection Week: Western Cape to appoint children\u2019s commissioner], ''The South African'', 3 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref><ref>Petersen, Tammy. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/child-murder-capital-to-introduce-first-childrens-commissioner-20190610 Child murder capital to introduce first Children\u2019s Commissioner], ''News24'', 10 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref> In March 2020, the provincial parliament recommended rights activist Christina Nomdo for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tembo |first1=Theolin |title=Legislature paves way to appoint Christina Nomdo as Western Cape Commissioner of Children |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/legislature-paves-way-to-appoint-christina-nomdo-as-western-cape-commissioner-of-children-45202798 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 March 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nNational Police Minister [[Bheki Cele]] announced on 11 July 2019, that the [[South African National Defence Force]] (SANDF) would be deployed in the gang-ridden areas of [[Cape Town]]. Winde welcomed the deployment of SANDF. His predecessor, [[Helen Zille]], had repeatedly asked for the deployment of SANDF during her tenure. The deployment came into effect on 18 July 2019 and was set to end on 16 September 2019. However, Winde wrote to President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] and Defence Minister [[Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula]] in mid-September 2019 to request that the SANDF deployment in [[Cape Town]] be extended.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sandfs-deployment-to-cape-flats-cabinet-to-assess-situation-after-premier-winde-calls-for-an-extension-20190910 SANDF's deployment to Cape Flats: Cabinet to 'assess situation' after Premier Winde calls for an extension], ''News24'', 10 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> Winde reasoned that an extension of the army is required to bring stability to the communities.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/still-a-massive-hill-to-climb-windes-reasons-for-wanting-army-to-stay-extra-6-months-20190911 'Still a massive hill to climb' - Winde's reasons for wanting army to stay extra 6 months], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The cabinet granted the request and is now set to end in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-fritz-welcome-sandfs-extended-stay-but-want-to-see-a-few-changes-20190916 Winde, Fritz welcome SANDF's extended stay, but want to see a few changes], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-sandfs-deployment-in-western-cape-extended-to-march-2020-20190916 SANDF's deployment in Western Cape extended to March 2020], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde delivered his maiden [[State of the Province Address (South Africa)|State of the Province Address]] on 18 July 2019, in which he highlighted the provincial government's achievements and outlined his agenda.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/07/18/job-creation-gangs-likely-to-feature-in-premier-winde-s-sopa Job creation, gangs likely to feature in Premier Winde's Sopa], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 17 August 2019.</ref> Also in the speech, Winde placed emphasis on the [[Crime in South Africa|provincial crime and misconduct statistics]] and claimed that the police \"had lost the war on crime\" because of [[South African Police Service#Criticism and controversies|mismanagement]].<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2156487/police-have-lost-the-war-on-crime-in-the-western-cape-says-winde/ Police have lost the war on crime in the Western Cape, says Winde], ''The Citizen'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-govt-mulling-court-action-over-control-of-saps-in-province-20190718 Western Cape govt mulling court action over control of SAPS in province], ''News24'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2019, he appointed Harry Malila as the new Director-General of the Western Cape Provincial Government. Malila succeeded long-serving Brent Gerber.<ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Harry Malila appointed as Western Cape director-general |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-harry-malila-appointed-as-western-cape-director-general-35615157 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=22 October 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020, Winde delivered his second State of the Province Address at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]]. It was the first time that the SOPA was held outside of the Provincial Parliament's chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gitahu |first1=Mwangi |title=Focus on Western Cape Sopa at Mitchells Plain centre |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/focus-on-western-cape-sopa-at-mitchells-plain-centre-43010777 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and record==\n===Immigration===\nWinde had been critical of controversial immigration regulations introduced by the national government, which he alleged had harmed tourism growth in the Western Cape. In response, he organised petitions against the regulations.<ref>[https://www.nwivisas.com/nwi-blog/south-africa/mec-alan-winde-plans-to-petition-visa-regulations/ MEC Alan Winde plans to petition visa regulations], ''nwvisas''. Retrieved on 7 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.vocfm.co.za/regulations-detrimental-to-economy-winde/ Regulations detrimental to economy: Winde], ''Voice of the Cape'', 3 September 2014. Retrieved on 3 July 2019.</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nProvincial government officials visited clothing factories in the Cape Town area on 11 June 2012. Winde investigated a local government leadership programme. The specific programme aimed to give the unemployed youth work experience.<ref>Adams, Nathan. [https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/11/Winde-visits-clothing-factories Winde visits clothing factories], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 June 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde approached the [[Development Bank of South Africa]] on 31 July 2012 to secure funding for the provincial government's work and skill programme. The programme has been active since 2009. Winde announced that if the provincial government could acquire additional funding, an extra 600 young people would be able to benefit from this project.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2012/07/31/WC-Skills-programme-needs-funding WC skills programme needs funding], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 July 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe visited small businesses in the Cape Town CBD on 15 January 2013. He called on the businesses to enter the province's Entrepreneurship Recognition Awards.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/01/15/Winde-promotes-Entrepreneurship-Awards Winde promotes Entrepreneurship Awards], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 15 January 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Western Cape Economic Development Department launched an artisan development programme on 20 August 2013 to train more artisans. Winde said that his department would be putting special focus on crucial industries in the province.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/08/20/Qualified-artisans-have-become-scarce 'Qualified artisans are scarce'], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 August 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Premier Helen Zille led a delegation to China in November 2015 in a bid to secure increased trade and investment opportunities. A report from 2013 estimated that the province's exports to China were valued at over [[South African rand|R]]2 billion (US$131.8 million).<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/11/13/Zille-Winde-lead-delegation-to-China Zille, Winde to lead delegation to China], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 13 November 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe said on 10 October 2018 that youth unemployment should be the main focus of the national job and employment summit, hosted by the [[Government of South Africa|national government]]. The Provincial Department of Economic Development has initiated many employment projects aiming to employ the unemployed youth.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/04/job-summit-can-t-be-allowed-to-become-another-talk-shop Youth unemployment must be key focus of job summit - Alan Winde], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 4 October 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde has been commended for creating a business-friendly environment in the Western Cape since the provincial economy has performed better than the national growth rate.<ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> The Western Cape currently has a lower unemployment rate compared to the national average. Democratic Alliance Federal Leader [[Mmusi Maimane]] called Winde the \"premier of jobs\", when he announced him as the party's candidate.<ref>Mpahlele, Mary Jane. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-premier-candidate-alan-winde-to-focus-on-job-creation-housing-17144485 DA Premier candidate Alan Winde to focus on job creation, housing], ''IOL'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He has even received praise for his economic policies from senior opposition politicians. Deputy President of South Africa and senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] figure [[David Mabuza]] said in September 2019 that the provincial government's economic policies should be implemented in other ANC-run provinces.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-11-da-premier-alan-winde-gets-surprise-endorsement-from-david-mabuza/ DA premier Alan Winde gets surprise endorsement from David Mabuza], ''TimesLIVE'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019</ref><ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/mabuza-praises-winde-as-a-good-selection-says-plans-are-afoot-to-settle-people-in-the-western-cape-20190911 Mabuza praises Winde as a 'good selection', says plans are afoot to settle people in the Western Cape], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political infighting and corruption===\nDemocratic Alliance party insiders have described Winde as someone who is not involved in party infighting and prioritised on completing his work.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. \n [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 7 April 2019. \"Winde is largely seen within the party as someone who is focused on his job and does not get involved in political infighting.\"</ref>\n\nDuring his premiership, Winde has strongly opposed corruption. He made it mandatory for his provincial ministers to undergo lifestyle audits. He announced in August 2019 that he would probe all the corruption allegations made against his provincial ministers. He made this announcement after the official opposition [[African National Congress]] had called for an investigation into alleged misconduct by the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Winde vows to probe all corruption allegation against MECs |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/30/winde-vows-to-probe-all-corruption-allegation-against-mecs | newspaper=EWN|accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nFollowing Winde's deployment to the Community Safety Department in November 2018, he announced that revised technology would be used to prevent and reduce crime. In the same month, he met with Hanover Park Peace Ambassador, Riedwaan Samuels, who was shot four times in the leg. Winde praised all the young peace ambassadors who were standing up against gang violence and fighting for their communities to be safer. He also met with Western Cape Police Commissioner, Khombinkosi Jula, and discussed that the addition of new police officers would help with the police under-resourcing in the Western Cape.<ref>Maliti, Soyiso. [https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/news/windes-plan-to-fight-crime-using-tech-17759673 Winde's plan to fight crime using tech], ''IOL'', 3 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Mlamla, Sisonke. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/pics-praise-for-hanover-park-peace-ambassador-who-was-shot-17791173 PICS: Praise for Hanover Park Peace Ambassador who was shot], ''IOL'', 6 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/11/09/wc-police-service-boosted-by-addition-of-1-000-new-recruits WC police service boosted by addition of 1,000 new recruits], ''EWN'', 9 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Winde called for the establishment of a provincial police force. In mid-December, [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] farmers requested that the Provincial Community Safety Department allocate more police officers to the area. In response, the Provincial Community Safety Department wrote a letter to the Western Cape Police Commissioner.<ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-wants-provincial-police-force-for-western-cape-20181213 Winde wants provincial police force for Western Cape], ''News24'', 13 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/12/18/philippi-urge-mec-alan-winde-to-urgently-allocate-them-more-police Philippi farmers urge MEC Winde to urgently allocate them more police], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government formally declared an inter-governmental dispute with National Minister of Police [[Bheki Cele]] on 29 April 2019 over police resources allocated to the province.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-04-28-western-cape-government-declares-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-policing/ Western Cape government declares dispute with Bheki Cele over policing], ''TimesLIVE'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/crime/2123896/western-cape-government-declares-formal-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-police-resourcing-da/ Western Cape government declares formal dispute with Bheki Cele over police resourcing \u2013 DA], ''TheCitizen'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref>\n\nSANDF was deployed to the areas of [[Cape Town]] affected by high levels of crime and gang violence in July 2019. Winde welcomed the decision by the [[Department of Defence (South Africa)|National Department of Defence]] to assist the police in its efforts to reduce the city's crime statistics.<ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/go-in-arrest-those-gangsters-w-cape-premier-on-military-move-20190711 Go in, arrest those gangsters: W Cape premier on military move], ''News24'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref><ref>Mabuza, Ernest. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-11-police-minister-bheki-cele-deploys-army-to-crime-ridden-western-cape/ Police minister Bheki Cele deploys army to crime-ridden Western Cape], ''BusinessDay'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref> The deployment was extended in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/winde-welcomes-sandf-extension-but-wants-criminal-justice-system-fixed-33080728 Winde welcomes SANDF extension but wants criminal justice system fixed], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Provincial Minister of Community Safety [[Albert Fritz]] announced on 19 September 2019 that the provincial government would annually be investing R1 billion (US$67.3 million) for three years into the training and deployment of 3,000 safety officers and 150 investigators. A total of 500 safety officers were deployed in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC provincial police service set to be deployed in February |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/05/wc-provincial-police-service-set-to-be-deployed-in-february |accessdate=14 December 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=500 new law enforcement officers deployed to crime hot spots in Cape Town |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/500-new-law-enforcement-officers-deployed-to-crime-hot-spots-in-cape-town-20200210 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The safety plan aims to halve the province's crime statistics within the next decade. Fritz added that the provincial government would also establish an integrated violence prevention programme. The provincial ministers would also be assessed by key performance indicators (KPIs) related to the safety plan.<ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/windes-r1bn-safety-plan-3-000-new-law-enforcement-officers-150-investigators-20190919 Winde's R1bn safety plan: 3 000 new law enforcement officers, 150 investigators], ''News24'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>Buhle, Lindwa. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/premier-winde-announces-western-cape-most-expensive-safety-plan/ Western Cape\u2019s crime-fighting plan: R1-billion, 3000 new officers and more], ''The South African'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.702.co.za/articles/361338/winde-to-appoint-3000-new-officers-in-three-year-wc-safety-plan Winde to appoint 3000 new officers in three-year WC safety plan], ''www.702.co.za'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Agriculture and tourism===\nOne of his duties, as Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities, was to oversee the Tourism Department of the Western Cape Government. He was responsible for projects such as Project Khulisa, a project introduced by the provincial government to increase tourism growth and grow the South African economy. The project resulted in the Western Cape tourism sector growing extensively.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/09/01/WC-Govt-launch-economic-growth-plan WC govt launches economic growth plan], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 1 September 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced that it was investing more than R23 million (US$1.5 million) on increasing the province's agricultural exports and set a target of creating 100,000 jobs in the sector. Winde said that additional support would be given to emerging farmers.<ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/30/WC-govt-invests-over-R23m-on-increasing-agricultural-exports WC govt invests over R23m on increasing agricultural exports], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/31/WC-govt-to-create-more-than-100-thousand-jobs-in-agricultural-sector WC to create over 100,000 jobs in agricultural sector], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cape Town water crisis|drought]] that ravaged the Western Cape province from 2017 to 2018, he argued for farmers to keep hold of their private agricultural water supply, even if their local municipalities had a shortage of water.<ref>Head, Tom. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-alan-winde-western-cape-premier/ Breaking: Alan Winde revealed as the DA\u2019s choice for Western Cape premier], ''The South African'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nDuring a campaign visit to the West Coast region of the Western Cape province on 8 January 2019, Winde urged communities to protect infrastructure. He made this announcement after he witnessed fire-damaged municipal buildings in the town of [[Saldanha Bay]]. The buildings were set on fire during violent protests that occurred in 2018.<ref>Brandt, Kevin. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/01/08/da-wc-premier-candidate-winde-embarks-door-to-door-campaign Winde urges communities to protect infrastructure during door-to-door campaign], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 8 January 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nWinde called for the Western Cape to draw its electricity from natural resources and be independent of [[Eskom|Eskom's]] electricity supply in March 2019.<ref>Mokone, Thabo. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-03-02-da-wants-western-cape-off-eskom-grid/ DA wants Western Cape off Eskom grid], ''TimesLIVE'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref> He said that it is his ambition for the City of Cape Town to become the first city in South Africa to procure electricity from independent suppliers.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/20/alan-winde-says-eskom-crisis-will-cripple-sa-s-economy DA's Winde hopes CT can be the first to get power from independent suppliers], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[Eskom]] announced another round of [[2007\u20132019 South African energy crisis|power outages]]. Winde described the announcement as the \"last straw\" and called on Minister of Energy [[Gwede Mantashe]] to consider a proposal in which municipalities obtain electricity directly from IPPs.<ref>Mabuza, Ernst. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-10-17-alan-winde-asks-gwede-mantashe-to-allow-municipalities-to-procure-clean-energy/ Alan Winde asks Gwede Mantashe to allow municipalities to procure clean energy], ''TimesLIVE'', 17 October 2019. Retrieved on 17 October 2019.</ref> Mantashe, later on, agreed to discuss the matter.<ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-11-19-gwede-mantashe-opens-a-gap-will-discuss-independent-power-for-western-cape/ Gwede Mantashe opens a gap - will 'discuss' independent power for Western Cape], ''SowetanLIVE'', 19 November 2019. Retrieved on 6 December 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, President Ramaphosa announced in his State of the Nation Address that municipalities with an adequate financial standing would be allowed to purchase electricity from IPPs. Winde welcomed the decision and called for it to be expedited.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brandt |first1=Kevin |title=WC Premier Winde looking to quickly implement Ramaphosa's IPP announcement |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/02/14/wc-premier-winde-looking-to-quickly-implement-ramaphosa-s-ipp-announcement-1 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alan Winde}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/alan-winde/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/profile/mr-alan-winde Provincial Minister of Community Safety]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/97 Premier of the Western Cape: Overview]\n* [https://cfo.co.za/article/alan-winde Profile: Alan Winde] at CFO South Africa\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/alan-winde Alan Winde, Mr] at [[Government of South Africa]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Helen Zille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Plato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fritz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=''Position established''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Garth Strachan}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Position dissolved''}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{WCPremiers}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winde, Alan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from Knysna]]\n[[Category:South African businesspeople]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Premiers of the Western Cape]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Alan Winde\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Western Cape)|MPP]]\n| image               = Alan Winde.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Winde in 2018\n| office              = 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]\n| status              = \n| premier             = \n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Helen Zille]]\n| succeeding          = \n| successor           = \n| office1             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]\n| premier1            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start1         = 1 November 2018\n| term_end1           = 22 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Dan Plato]]\n| successor1          = [[Albert Fritz]]\n| office2             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]\n| premier2            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start2         = 26 May 2014\n| term_end2           = 1 November 2018\n| alongside2          = \n| constituency2       = \n| predecessor2        = ''Position established''\n| successor2          = [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] \n| majority2           = \n| prior_term2         =\n| office3             = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]\n| premier3            = [[Helen Zille]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2009\n| term_end3           = 26 May 2014\n| alongside3          = \n| constituency3       = \n| predecessor3        = Garth Strachan\n| successor3          = ''Position dissolved''\n| majority3           = \n| prior_term3         =\n| office4            = [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start4        = 15 June 1999\n| birthname          = Alan Richard Winde\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Knysna]], [[Cape Province]], [[South Africa]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = [[South Africa]]n\n| party              = [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (2000\u2013present)\n| otherparty         = [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] (1999\u20132000) <br />[[Independent politician|Independent]] (Before 1999)\n| spouse             = Tracy Winde (m. 1993)\n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = 2\n| residence          = [[Knysna]]<br />[[Cape Town]]\n| education          = Knysna High School\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician<br />Businessman\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Alan Richard Winde''' (born 18 March 1965) is a South African politician and previous businessman.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', Western Cape, 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 30 September 2018.</ref> He is currently serving as the 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]] since his election in 2019, and a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] since 1999. He previously served as the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]], the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]] and the [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]. Winde is a member of the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]] (DA).\n\nBorn in [[Knysna]], Winde attended Knysna High School. He has experience as a businessman and entrepreneur since he established several businesses. He also worked for and managed numerous companies. He started his political career as a municipal and district councillor in the early 1990s. Shortly afterwards in 1999, he was elected to the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He has held various leadership positions in the Democratic Alliance provincial parliament caucus. Winde was appointed [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]] in May 2009 and served until May 2014, when he assumed the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-08-zille-appoints-western-cape-cabinet Zille appoints Western Cape Cabinet], ''Mail & Guardian''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref><ref>Williams, Murray. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/premier-zilles-new-cape-cabinet-1691800 Premier Zille\u2019s new Cape cabinet], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the Democratic Alliance selected Winde to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-named-da-candidate-to-take-over-from-helen-zille-as-premier/ Alan Winde named DA candidate to take over from Helen Zille as premier], ''TimesLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref> In October 2018, Premier [[Helen Zille]] appointed Winde to the post of [[Government of the Western Cape|Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]. He took office on 1 November 2018.\n\nOn 8 May 2019, the Democratic Alliance retained their majority in the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]], but with a decrease in the number of seats.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-10-democratic-alliance-officially-wins-the-western-cape-vote/ It's official: The Democratic Alliance has won the Western Cape], ''TimesLIVE'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> Winde was elected Premier on 22 May 2019 and succeeded Helen Zille. He is the second Western Cape Premier from the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Le Roux |first1=Nckey |title=Winde formally elected as Premier on 22 May |url=https://www.georgeherald.com/News/Article/Elections-2019/premier-elect-inaugurated-on-22-may-201905131129 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=George Herald |date=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and business career==\n===Family and personal life===\nWinde was born on 18 March 1965 in the town of [[Knysna]]. He attended and matriculated from Knysna High School. He married Tracy Winde in 1993. They have two children named Lauren and Jason.<ref name = \"onesaforall\">[https://www.onesouthafricaforall.co.za/ Alan Winde], ''Democratic Alliance''. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde's father, William Dave Winde, died on 1 August 2019.<ref>(In Afrikaans) [https://www.son.co.za/Nuus/Suid-Kaap/premier-se-pa-oorlede-20190801 Winde se pa oorlede], ''Son Digitaal'', 1 August 2019. Retrieved on 1 August 2019.</ref>\n\n===Business career===\nWinde has experience as an entrepreneur. He established and managed many small businesses. He was also a director of a tour company and a business broker with Aldes Business Brokers.<ref name=\"onesaforall\" />\n\n==Early political career==\n[[File:Minister Alan Winde (cropped).jpg|x200px|thumb|left|Winde as Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism in 2013]]\nWinde ran as an independent candidate and was elected to the South Cape District Council in 1996. He had previously served as a councillor for the Outeniqua Rural Council. Shortly after being elected a district councillor, the [[Democratic Party (South Africa)|Democratic Party]] recruited him to be a candidate for the [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]. He was elected in the [[1999 South African general election|general election of 1999]].<ref name =\"bizzabo\">[https://events.bizzabo.com/u-start-conference-africa/agenda/speakers/89264 Alan Winde - Bizzabo], ''U-Start Conference Africa''. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe took office as a Member on 15 June 2009. During his first term, he served as Western Cape Provincial Finance Chairman and a Member of the Executive Committee. He returned to the Provincial Parliament following the 2004 general election. Briefly, before being re-elected in 2009, he served as Chief Whip of the Official Opposition, Party Spokesperson on Environment and Planning and Deputy Party Spokesperson on Economic Development and Tourism.<ref name=\"bizzabo\" />\n\nPremier Helen Zille appointed Winde to the position of Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism following his re-election in May 2009. Constitutional Court Judge [[Yvonne Mokgoro]] swore him in as Provincial Minister on 7 May 2009. He consequently succeeded Garth Strachan.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/appointment-western-cape-provincial-cabinet Appointment of the Western Cape Provincial Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 7 May 2009. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter the 2014 elections, Premier Helen Zille announced that Winde would now hold the title of Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities and only lead the Provincial Departments of Agriculture, Economic Development and Tourism. The Provincial Finance Department would be an independent department with its own Provincial Minister. Western Cape Deputy Judge President Jeanette Traverso swore him in on 26 May 2014.<ref>[https://www.westerncape.gov.za/news/premier-helen-zille-announces-new-cabinet Premier Helen Zille Announces New Cabinet], ''Western Cape Government'', 21 May 2014. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Winde was selected by the DA's Federal Executive to be the party's Western Cape Premier candidate for the 2019 provincial election.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-da-names-alan-winde-western-cape-premier-candidate WATCH: DA names Alan Winde as Western Cape Premier candidate], ''eNCA'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nPremier Helen Zille announced in October 2018 that Winde would move to the Provincial Community Safety Department as incumbent Provincial Minister [[Dan Plato]] had announced his intention to resign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thaw |first1=Regan |title=Alan Winde to take over WC Community Safety portfolio |url=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=19 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/19/alan-winde-to-take-over-wc-community-safety-portfolio |archivedate=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alan Winde replacing Dan Plato as community safety MEC |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/alan-winde-replacing-dan-plato-as-community-safety-mec-17553379 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> Winde was succeeded by [[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]] on 1 November 2018. He subsequently assumed the post of Provincial Minister of Community Safety.<ref>{{cite news |title=Western Cape Economic Development on swearing in of MEC Beverley Sch\u00e4fer |url=https://www.gov.za/speeches/western-cape-economic-development-swearing-mec-beverley-sch%C3%A4fer-1-nov-2018-0000 |accessdate=30 August 2019 |publisher=South African Government |date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nWinde has served as acting Premier of the Western Cape on various brief occasions.<ref>[https://twitter.com/alanwinde/status/1092696090162446337 Alan Winde on Twitter: \"I have just been sworn in as Acting Premier. I agreed with the Judge not to invade any neighboring country.\"]. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He represented the provincial government at the [[State of the Nation Address (South Africa)|February 2019 State of the Nation Address]], as [[Helen Zille]] was in [[Germany]].<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sona-2019-from-thuma-mina-to-new-dawn-fades-as-bosasa-casts-a-shadow-20190208 SONA 2019: From 'Thuma Mina' to 'New Dawn Fades' as Bosasa casts a shadow], News24, 8 February 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n== Premier of the Western Cape (2019\u2013present)==\n===Campaign===\n{{see also|2019 Western Cape provincial election}}\n[[File:Alan Winde For Premier Campaign Bus 2019 (cropped).jpg|270px|thumb|Alan Winde for Premier campaign bus, which was unveiled in April 2019.]]\nWinde emerged as the front-runner quite early on in the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=Who wants to be the Western Cape's next |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/who-wants-to-be-the-western-capes-next-premier-15527764 |accessdate=28 August 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=18 June 2018}}</ref> On 19 September 2018, Democratic Alliance Federal Leader, [[Mmusi Maimane]], announced Winde as the party's Western Cape Premier candidate to succeed Premier [[Helen Zille]] after the 2019 elections. Winde defeated prominent candidates such as the Provincial Leader of the Democratic Alliance in the Western Cape [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]], and Member of Parliament [[David Maynier]]. After the announcement, Madikizela endorsed Winde and offered his full support to Winde's campaign.<ref>Ngcobo, Khanyisile. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/western-cape/alan-winde-named-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-17141423 Alan Winde named DA's Western Cape premier candidate], ''[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]'', [[Western Cape]], 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Dentlinger, Lindsay. [https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/featured/da-wc-leader-bonginkosi-madikizela-backs-alan-winde-as-premier-candidate/ar-BBNA1TB DA WC leader Bonginkosi Madikizela backs Alan Winde as premier candidate], ''MSN'', 20 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance launched their campaign to retain the Western Cape after the 2019 elections at the [[Cape Town Stadium]] on 29 September 2018. At the event, Mmusi Maimane highlighted the party's achievements while governing the province, such as the province's low unemployment rate and that the party had turned the previously struggling Provincial Education Department into one of the best functioning departments in South Africa.<ref>Isaacs, Lauren. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/09/30/da-determined-to-retain-western-cape-in-2019-elections DA determined to retain Western Cape in 2019 elections],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref><ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/unity-the-rallying-call-for-western-cape-da-as-it-launches-its-election-campaign-20180929 Unity the rallying call for Western Cape DA, as it launches its election campaign], ''News24'', 29 September 2018. Retrieved on 9 February 2019.</ref>\n\nAfter he was announced as the premier candidate, Winde embarked on a listening tour and travelled to various communities in the [[Western Cape]].<ref>[https://pr.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-DA-Western-Cape-Premier-Candidate-Winde-takes-Listening-Tour-to-George-8001073 #WindeForPremier: DA Western Cape Premier Candidate Winde takes Listening Tour to George], ''African News Agency'', 12 November 2018. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nHe also campaigned for local DA candidates in by-elections. For instance, he went to the community of De Doorns to campaign for a DA candidate in a hotly-contested by-election. The DA candidate, Luwellyn Willemse, retained ward 3 of the [[Breede Valley Local Municipality|Breede Valley municipality]] by earning a total of 1,101 votes (52.16%).<ref>{{cite news |title=DA retains ward in Breede Valley municipal by-election |url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/2027939/da-retains-ward-in-breede-valley-municipal-by-election/ |accessdate=30 August 2019 |newspaper=The Citizen |date=25 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.africannewsagency.com/pr-wire/WindeForPremier-Alan-Winde-to-address-supporters-at-De-Doorns-final-rally-ahead-of-by-election-7777913 #WindeForPremier: Alan Winde to address supporters at De Doorns final rally ahead of by-election], ''African News Agency''. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde launched the Democratic Alliance's 2019 provincial voter registration campaign on 4 January 2019. Winde and other Democratic Alliance members erected party registration posters in [[Mitchells Plain]], ahead of the Independent Electoral Commission's registration weekend on 26 and 27 January 2019.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-winde-launches-das-campaign-voter-registration-plan-criticised-18686993 WATCH: Winde launches DA's campaign, voter registration plan criticised], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 5 August 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance held its provincial Plan of Action Rally on 2 March 2019 at the [[Bellville Velodrome]] and launched their provincial party manifesto. Winde and various other DA politicians addressed thousands of party supporters. Winde assured that he would take on the national government for the Western Cape to receive its own, decentralised [[Rail transport in South Africa|rail]] and [[South African Police Service|police service]]. He pledged to increase the availability of [[Housing voucher|housing vouchers]] and vowed to spend [[Taxation in South Africa|tax money]] properly.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/da-comes-out-guns-blazing-to-retain-control-of-wc DA comes out guns blazing to retain control of WC], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref><ref>Payne, Sune. [https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-03-04-da-punts-control-of-rail-and-policing-in-western-cape-as-party-launches-provincial-manifesto/ DA punts control of rail and policing in Western Cape as party launches provincial manifesto], ''The Daily Maverick'', 4 March 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref><ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/02/maimane-unemployment-will-continue-to-rise-the-longer-anc-stays-in-power Maimane: Unemployment will continue to rise the longer ANC stays in power],  Cape Town, ''EWN'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde vowed on 11 March 2019 to build a police station in the gang-riddled community of [[Bonteheuwel]] due to the large number of murders that occur in the suburb.<ref>Mortlock, Monique.  \n[https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/11/winde-promises-to-a-police-station-in-bonteheuwel-if-da-wins-elections Winde promises to build police station in Bonteheuwel if DA wins elections], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde participated in the first [[eNCA]] Town Hall Debate, hosted at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]] on 14 March 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/watch-emotions-run-high-encas-town-hall-debate WATCH: Emotions run high at eNCA's Town Hall Debate], ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref> The debate included many senior Western Cape politicians, such as former African National Congress Premier [[Ebrahim Rasool]], Economic Freedom Fighters City of Cape Town councillor [[Melikhaya Xego]], Good Party Leader [[Patricia de Lille]], and Freedom Front Plus Western Cape Premier candidate [[Peter Marais]].<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/senior-politicians-trade-barbs-campaign-at-enca-townhall-debate-in-the-capes-mitchells-plain-20190314 Senior politicians trade barbs, campaign at eNCA townhall debate in the Cape's Mitchells Plain], ''News24'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/live-video-cape-town-pre-election-town-hall-meetings WATCH: eNCA Town Hall Debate - Cape Town], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 March 2019.  Retrieved on 18 March 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and [[Mmusi Maimane]] revealed the Democratic Alliance's alternative energy plan for the Western Cape on 27 March 2019, in which the province acquires electricity directly from Independent Power Producers (IPPs).<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-maimane-winde-reveal-das-alternative-energy-plan-20115500 WATCH: Maimane, Winde reveal DA's alternative energy plan], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 27 March 2019. Retrieved on 28 March 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Democratic Alliance retained control of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, but with a decrease in the number of seats, on 8 May 2019.<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/elections/2128368/live-da-secures-majority-again-in-western-cape-election-results/ LIVE: DA secures majority again in Western Cape election results], ''The Citizen'', 10 May 2019. Retrieved on 10 May 2019.</ref> The party celebrated their election win in the province on 16 May 2019.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/elections/news/campaigning-a-reality-check-das-winde-admits-as-he-thanks-the-western-cape-20190516 Campaigning a 'reality check', DA's Winde admits as he thanks the Western Cape], ''News24'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved on 18 May 2019.</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWinde was elected Premier of the Western Cape on 22 May 2019 during the first sitting of the Sixth Provincial Parliament. He received 24 out of the 34 valid votes. Six ballots were spoilt, and there were two abstentions. His main challenger for the post was [[Cameron Dugmore]] of the [[African National Congress]], who received only 10 out of the 34 valid votes.<ref>Lee, Samantha. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Local/Peoples-Post/breaking-winde-sworn-in-as-western-cape-premier-20190522 Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''News24'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 22 May 2019.</ref><ref>Mortlock, Monique. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/05/22/da-s-winde-elected-as-new-wc-premier DA's Winde elected as new WC premier], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/politics/2133822/winde-elected-western-cape-premier/ Winde elected Western Cape premier], ''The Citizen'', 22 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde announced the formation of his Provincial Cabinet on 23 May 2019. He retained four ministers in their existing portfolios, while he moved three to other portfolios and appointed three new members. He appointed former DA Member of Parliament and premier candidate contender, [[David Maynier]], to the post of Provincial Minister of Finance and Economic Opportunities, while he moved [[Albert Fritz]] and [[Ivan Meyer]] to the posts of Provincial Minister of Community Safety and Provincial Minister of Agriculture, respectively. Winde also said that all the newly-appointed cabinet members would undergo lifestyle audits.<ref>Sicetsha, Andile. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/western-cape-premier-alan-winde-new-cabinet/ Western Cape Premier Alan Winde announces new Cabinet], ''The South African'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 9 September 2019.</ref><ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-23-western-cape-premier-alan-windes-cabinet-a-mix-of-old-and-new/ Western Cape premier Alan Winde's cabinet a mix of old and new], ''TimesLVE'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 23 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-names-western-cape-cabinet-20190523 Winde names new Western Cape cabinet], ''News24'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>Nkanjeni, Unathi. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-24-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-western-cape-provincial-cabinet/ What you need to know about the Western Cape provincial cabinet], ''TimesLIVE'', 24 May 2019. Retrieved on 25 May 2019.</ref><ref>Kiewit, Lester. [https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-23-windes-cabinet-to-undergo-lifestyle-audits Winde\u2019s cabinet to undergo lifestyle audits], ''Mail & Guardian'', 23 May 2019. Retrieved on 8 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde confirmed on 3 June 2019 that a provincial children's commissioner would be appointed before the end of 2019 or in early 2020. He added that the commissioner would have the authority to monitor, investigate, research, lobby and educate on issues, policy, services and legislation that affect children.<ref>Kahla, Cheryl. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/child-protection-week-western-cape-to-childrens-commissioner-2019/ Child Protection Week: Western Cape to appoint children\u2019s commissioner], ''The South African'', 3 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref><ref>Petersen, Tammy. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/child-murder-capital-to-introduce-first-childrens-commissioner-20190610 Child murder capital to introduce first Children\u2019s Commissioner], ''News24'', 10 June 2019. Retrieved on 13 June 2019.</ref> In March 2020, the provincial parliament recommended rights activist Christina Nomdo for the position.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tembo |first1=Theolin |title=Legislature paves way to appoint Christina Nomdo as Western Cape Commissioner of Children |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/legislature-paves-way-to-appoint-christina-nomdo-as-western-cape-commissioner-of-children-45202798 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=19 March 2020 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nNational Police Minister [[Bheki Cele]] announced on 11 July 2019, that the [[South African National Defence Force]] (SANDF) would be deployed in the gang-ridden areas of [[Cape Town]]. Winde welcomed the deployment of SANDF. His predecessor, [[Helen Zille]], had repeatedly asked for the deployment of SANDF during her tenure. The deployment came into effect on 18 July 2019 and was set to end on 16 September 2019. However, Winde wrote to President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] and Defence Minister [[Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula]] in mid-September 2019 to request that the SANDF deployment in [[Cape Town]] be extended.<ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sandfs-deployment-to-cape-flats-cabinet-to-assess-situation-after-premier-winde-calls-for-an-extension-20190910 SANDF's deployment to Cape Flats: Cabinet to 'assess situation' after Premier Winde calls for an extension], ''News24'', 10 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> Winde reasoned that an extension of the army is required to bring stability to the communities.<ref>Etheridge, Jenna. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/still-a-massive-hill-to-climb-windes-reasons-for-wanting-army-to-stay-extra-6-months-20190911 'Still a massive hill to climb' - Winde's reasons for wanting army to stay extra 6 months], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The cabinet granted the request and is now set to end in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-fritz-welcome-sandfs-extended-stay-but-want-to-see-a-few-changes-20190916 Winde, Fritz welcome SANDF's extended stay, but want to see a few changes], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/just-in-sandfs-deployment-in-western-cape-extended-to-march-2020-20190916 SANDF's deployment in Western Cape extended to March 2020], ''News24'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde delivered his maiden [[State of the Province Address (South Africa)|State of the Province Address]] on 18 July 2019, in which he highlighted the provincial government's achievements and outlined his agenda.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/07/18/job-creation-gangs-likely-to-feature-in-premier-winde-s-sopa Job creation, gangs likely to feature in Premier Winde's Sopa], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 17 August 2019.</ref> Also in the speech, Winde placed emphasis on the [[Crime in South Africa|provincial crime and misconduct statistics]] and claimed that the police \"had lost the war on crime\" because of [[South African Police Service#Criticism and controversies|mismanagement]].<ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2156487/police-have-lost-the-war-on-crime-in-the-western-cape-says-winde/ Police have lost the war on crime in the Western Cape, says Winde], ''The Citizen'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref><ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-govt-mulling-court-action-over-control-of-saps-in-province-20190718 Western Cape govt mulling court action over control of SAPS in province], ''News24'', 18 July 2019. Retrieved on 18 July 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 22 October 2019, he appointed Harry Malila as the new Director-General of the Western Cape Provincial Government. Malila succeeded long-serving Brent Gerber.<ref>{{cite news |title=WATCH: Harry Malila appointed as Western Cape director-general |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/watch-harry-malila-appointed-as-western-cape-director-general-35615157 |accessdate=22 October 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=22 October 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 February 2020, Winde delivered his second State of the Province Address at the Rocklands Civic Centre in [[Mitchells Plain]]. It was the first time that the SOPA was held outside of the Provincial Parliament's chambers.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gitahu |first1=Mwangi |title=Focus on Western Cape Sopa at Mitchells Plain centre |url=https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/focus-on-western-cape-sopa-at-mitchells-plain-centre-43010777 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and record==\n===Immigration===\nWinde had been critical of controversial immigration regulations introduced by the national government, which he alleged had harmed tourism growth in the Western Cape. In response, he organised petitions against the regulations.<ref>[https://www.nwivisas.com/nwi-blog/south-africa/mec-alan-winde-plans-to-petition-visa-regulations/ MEC Alan Winde plans to petition visa regulations], ''nwvisas''. Retrieved on 7 April 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.vocfm.co.za/regulations-detrimental-to-economy-winde/ Regulations detrimental to economy: Winde], ''Voice of the Cape'', 3 September 2014. Retrieved on 3 July 2019.</ref>\n\n===Economy===\nProvincial government officials visited clothing factories in the Cape Town area on 11 June 2012. Winde investigated a local government leadership programme. The specific programme aimed to give the unemployed youth work experience.<ref>Adams, Nathan. [https://ewn.co.za/2012/06/11/Winde-visits-clothing-factories Winde visits clothing factories], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 11 June 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde approached the [[Development Bank of South Africa]] on 31 July 2012 to secure funding for the provincial government's work and skill programme. The programme has been active since 2009. Winde announced that if the provincial government could acquire additional funding, an extra 600 young people would be able to benefit from this project.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2012/07/31/WC-Skills-programme-needs-funding WC skills programme needs funding], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 July 2012. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe visited small businesses in the Cape Town CBD on 15 January 2013. He called on the businesses to enter the province's Entrepreneurship Recognition Awards.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/01/15/Winde-promotes-Entrepreneurship-Awards Winde promotes Entrepreneurship Awards], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 15 January 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Western Cape Economic Development Department launched an artisan development programme on 20 August 2013 to train more artisans. Winde said that his department would be putting special focus on crucial industries in the province.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2013/08/20/Qualified-artisans-have-become-scarce 'Qualified artisans are scarce'], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 August 2013. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Premier Helen Zille led a delegation to China in November 2015 in a bid to secure increased trade and investment opportunities. A report from 2013 estimated that the province's exports to China were valued at over [[South African rand|R]]2 billion (US$131.8 million).<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/11/13/Zille-Winde-lead-delegation-to-China Zille, Winde to lead delegation to China], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 13 November 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nHe said on 10 October 2018 that youth unemployment should be the main focus of the national job and employment summit, hosted by the [[Government of South Africa|national government]]. The Provincial Department of Economic Development has initiated many employment projects aiming to employ the unemployed youth.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2018/10/04/job-summit-can-t-be-allowed-to-become-another-talk-shop Youth unemployment must be key focus of job summit - Alan Winde], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 4 October 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde has been commended for creating a business-friendly environment in the Western Cape since the provincial economy has performed better than the national growth rate.<ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> The Western Cape currently has a lower unemployment rate compared to the national average. Democratic Alliance Federal Leader [[Mmusi Maimane]] called Winde the \"premier of jobs\", when he announced him as the party's candidate.<ref>Mpahlele, Mary Jane. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-premier-candidate-alan-winde-to-focus-on-job-creation-housing-17144485 DA Premier candidate Alan Winde to focus on job creation, housing], ''IOL'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref> He has even received praise for his economic policies from senior opposition politicians. Deputy President of South Africa and senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] figure [[David Mabuza]] said in September 2019 that the provincial government's economic policies should be implemented in other ANC-run provinces.<ref>Makinana, Andisiwe. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-11-da-premier-alan-winde-gets-surprise-endorsement-from-david-mabuza/ DA premier Alan Winde gets surprise endorsement from David Mabuza], ''TimesLIVE'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019</ref><ref>Van Diemen, Ethan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/mabuza-praises-winde-as-a-good-selection-says-plans-are-afoot-to-settle-people-in-the-western-cape-20190911 Mabuza praises Winde as a 'good selection', says plans are afoot to settle people in the Western Cape], ''News24'', 11 September 2019. Retrieved on 17 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Political infighting and corruption===\nDemocratic Alliance party insiders have described Winde as someone who is not involved in party infighting and prioritised on completing his work.<ref>Mailovich, Claudi. \n [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/politics/2018-09-19-alan-winde-is-das-western-cape-premier-candidate-for-2019-elections/ Alan Winde\u2019s selection to DA top Cape job welcomed], ''BusinessLIVE'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 7 April 2019. \"Winde is largely seen within the party as someone who is focused on his job and does not get involved in political infighting.\"</ref>\n\nDuring his premiership, Winde has strongly opposed corruption. He made it mandatory for his provincial ministers to undergo lifestyle audits. He announced in August 2019 that he would probe all the corruption allegations made against his provincial ministers. He made this announcement after the official opposition [[African National Congress]] had called for an investigation into alleged misconduct by the Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works [[Bonginkosi Madikizela]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Winde vows to probe all corruption allegation against MECs |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/30/winde-vows-to-probe-all-corruption-allegation-against-mecs | newspaper=EWN|accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=30 August 2019 |location=Cape Town}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nFollowing Winde's deployment to the Community Safety Department in November 2018, he announced that revised technology would be used to prevent and reduce crime. In the same month, he met with Hanover Park Peace Ambassador, Riedwaan Samuels, who was shot four times in the leg. Winde praised all the young peace ambassadors who were standing up against gang violence and fighting for their communities to be safer. He also met with Western Cape Police Commissioner, Khombinkosi Jula, and discussed that the addition of new police officers would help with the police under-resourcing in the Western Cape.<ref>Maliti, Soyiso. [https://www.iol.co.za/weekend-argus/news/windes-plan-to-fight-crime-using-tech-17759673 Winde's plan to fight crime using tech], ''IOL'', 3 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Mlamla, Sisonke. [https://www.iol.co.za/capeargus/news/pics-praise-for-hanover-park-peace-ambassador-who-was-shot-17791173 PICS: Praise for Hanover Park Peace Ambassador who was shot], ''IOL'', 6 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/11/09/wc-police-service-boosted-by-addition-of-1-000-new-recruits WC police service boosted by addition of 1,000 new recruits], ''EWN'', 9 November 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Winde called for the establishment of a provincial police force. In mid-December, [[Philippi, Cape Town|Philippi]] farmers requested that the Provincial Community Safety Department allocate more police officers to the area. In response, the Provincial Community Safety Department wrote a letter to the Western Cape Police Commissioner.<ref>Gerber, Jan. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/winde-wants-provincial-police-force-for-western-cape-20181213 Winde wants provincial police force for Western Cape], ''News24'', 13 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Palm, Kaylynn. [https://ewn.co.za/2018/12/18/philippi-urge-mec-alan-winde-to-urgently-allocate-them-more-police Philippi farmers urge MEC Winde to urgently allocate them more police], Cape Town, ''Eyewitness News'', 18 December 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nThe provincial government formally declared an inter-governmental dispute with National Minister of Police [[Bheki Cele]] on 29 April 2019 over police resources allocated to the province.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-04-28-western-cape-government-declares-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-policing/ Western Cape government declares dispute with Bheki Cele over policing], ''TimesLIVE'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/crime/2123896/western-cape-government-declares-formal-dispute-with-bheki-cele-over-police-resourcing-da/ Western Cape government declares formal dispute with Bheki Cele over police resourcing \u2013 DA], ''TheCitizen'', 28 April 2019. Retrieved on 7 May 2019.</ref>\n\nSANDF was deployed to the areas of [[Cape Town]] affected by high levels of crime and gang violence in July 2019. Winde welcomed the decision by the [[Department of Defence (South Africa)|National Department of Defence]] to assist the police in its efforts to reduce the city's crime statistics.<ref>Evans, Jenni. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/go-in-arrest-those-gangsters-w-cape-premier-on-military-move-20190711 Go in, arrest those gangsters: W Cape premier on military move], ''News24'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref><ref>Mabuza, Ernest. [https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-07-11-police-minister-bheki-cele-deploys-army-to-crime-ridden-western-cape/ Police minister Bheki Cele deploys army to crime-ridden Western Cape], ''BusinessDay'', 11 July 2019. Retrieved on 13 July 2019.</ref> The deployment was extended in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/capetimes/news/winde-welcomes-sandf-extension-but-wants-criminal-justice-system-fixed-33080728 Winde welcomes SANDF extension but wants criminal justice system fixed], Cape Town, ''IOL'', 16 September 2019. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref>\n\nWinde and Provincial Minister of Community Safety [[Albert Fritz]] announced on 19 September 2019 that the provincial government would annually be investing R1 billion (US$67.3 million) for three years into the training and deployment of 3,000 safety officers and 150 investigators. A total of 500 safety officers were deployed in February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felix |first1=Jason |title=WC provincial police service set to be deployed in February |url=https://ewn.co.za/2019/12/05/wc-provincial-police-service-set-to-be-deployed-in-february |accessdate=14 December 2019 |newspaper=EWN |date=4 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Evans |first1=Jenni |title=500 new law enforcement officers deployed to crime hot spots in Cape Town |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/500-new-law-enforcement-officers-deployed-to-crime-hot-spots-in-cape-town-20200210 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The safety plan aims to halve the province's crime statistics within the next decade. Fritz added that the provincial government would also establish an integrated violence prevention programme. The provincial ministers would also be assessed by key performance indicators (KPIs) related to the safety plan.<ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/windes-r1bn-safety-plan-3-000-new-law-enforcement-officers-150-investigators-20190919 Winde's R1bn safety plan: 3 000 new law enforcement officers, 150 investigators], ''News24'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>Buhle, Lindwa. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/premier-winde-announces-western-cape-most-expensive-safety-plan/ Western Cape\u2019s crime-fighting plan: R1-billion, 3000 new officers and more], ''The South African'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref><ref>[http://www.702.co.za/articles/361338/winde-to-appoint-3000-new-officers-in-three-year-wc-safety-plan Winde to appoint 3000 new officers in three-year WC safety plan], ''www.702.co.za'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 23 September 2019.</ref>\n\n===Agriculture and tourism===\nOne of his duties, as Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities, was to oversee the Tourism Department of the Western Cape Government. He was responsible for projects such as Project Khulisa, a project introduced by the provincial government to increase tourism growth and grow the South African economy. The project resulted in the Western Cape tourism sector growing extensively.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2015/09/01/WC-Govt-launch-economic-growth-plan WC govt launches economic growth plan], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 1 September 2015. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the provincial government announced that it was investing more than R23 million (US$1.5 million) on increasing the province's agricultural exports and set a target of creating 100,000 jobs in the sector. Winde said that additional support would be given to emerging farmers.<ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/30/WC-govt-invests-over-R23m-on-increasing-agricultural-exports WC govt invests over R23m on increasing agricultural exports], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 30 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref><ref>Malgas, Natalie. [https://ewn.co.za/2016/03/31/WC-govt-to-create-more-than-100-thousand-jobs-in-agricultural-sector WC to create over 100,000 jobs in agricultural sector], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 31 March 2016. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cape Town water crisis|drought]] that ravaged the Western Cape province from 2017 to 2018, he argued for farmers to keep hold of their private agricultural water supply, even if their local municipalities had a shortage of water.<ref>Head, Tom. [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/who-is-alan-winde-western-cape-premier/ Breaking: Alan Winde revealed as the DA\u2019s choice for Western Cape premier], ''The South African'', 19 September 2018. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nDuring a campaign visit to the West Coast region of the Western Cape province on 8 January 2019, Winde urged communities to protect infrastructure. He made this announcement after he witnessed fire-damaged municipal buildings in the town of [[Saldanha Bay]]. The buildings were set on fire during violent protests that occurred in 2018.<ref>Brandt, Kevin. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/01/08/da-wc-premier-candidate-winde-embarks-door-to-door-campaign Winde urges communities to protect infrastructure during door-to-door campaign], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 8 January 2019. Retrieved on 10 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nWinde called for the Western Cape to draw its electricity from natural resources and be independent of [[Eskom|Eskom's]] electricity supply in March 2019.<ref>Mokone, Thabo. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-03-02-da-wants-western-cape-off-eskom-grid/ DA wants Western Cape off Eskom grid], ''TimesLIVE'', 2 March 2019. Retrieved on 3 March 2019.</ref> He said that it is his ambition for the City of Cape Town to become the first city in South Africa to procure electricity from independent suppliers.<ref>Felix, Jason. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/03/20/alan-winde-says-eskom-crisis-will-cripple-sa-s-economy DA's Winde hopes CT can be the first to get power from independent suppliers], Cape Town, ''EWN'', 20 March 2019. Retrieved on 20 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, [[Eskom]] announced another round of [[2007\u20132019 South African energy crisis|power outages]]. Winde described the announcement as the \"last straw\" and called on Minister of Energy [[Gwede Mantashe]] to consider a proposal in which municipalities obtain electricity directly from IPPs.<ref>Mabuza, Ernst. [https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-10-17-alan-winde-asks-gwede-mantashe-to-allow-municipalities-to-procure-clean-energy/ Alan Winde asks Gwede Mantashe to allow municipalities to procure clean energy], ''TimesLIVE'', 17 October 2019. Retrieved on 17 October 2019.</ref> Mantashe, later on, agreed to discuss the matter.<ref>Meyer, Dan. [https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2019-11-19-gwede-mantashe-opens-a-gap-will-discuss-independent-power-for-western-cape/ Gwede Mantashe opens a gap - will 'discuss' independent power for Western Cape], ''SowetanLIVE'', 19 November 2019. Retrieved on 6 December 2019.</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, President Ramaphosa announced in his State of the Nation Address that municipalities with an adequate financial standing would be allowed to purchase electricity from IPPs. Winde welcomed the decision and called for it to be expedited.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brandt |first1=Kevin |title=WC Premier Winde looking to quickly implement Ramaphosa's IPP announcement |url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/02/14/wc-premier-winde-looking-to-quickly-implement-ramaphosa-s-ipp-announcement-1 |accessdate=15 February 2020 |newspaper=EWN |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alan Winde}}\n* [https://www.pa.org.za/person/alan-winde/ People's Assembly profile]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/profile/mr-alan-winde Provincial Minister of Community Safety]\n* [https://www.westerncape.gov.za/your_gov/97 Premier of the Western Cape: Overview]\n* [https://cfo.co.za/article/alan-winde Profile: Alan Winde] at CFO South Africa\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/alan-winde Alan Winde, Mr] at [[Government of South Africa]]\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Helen Zille]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= 8th [[Premier of the Western Cape]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Plato]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Community Safety]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Albert Fritz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=''Position established''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Economic Opportunities]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beverley Sch\u00e4fer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Garth Strachan}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Finance, Economic Development and Tourism]]|years=2009\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Position dissolved''}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{SouthAfricaPremiers}}\n{{WCPremiers}}\n{{Winde provincial cabinet}}\n{{Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament}}\n{{Zille provincial cabinet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winde, Alan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:People from Knysna]]\n[[Category:South African businesspeople]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Democratic Alliance (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Premiers of the Western Cape]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTenure:Avoid refbombing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Winde"}
{"title_page": "Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen", "text_new": "The '''Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen''' is a member of the [[Helmholtz Association of German Research Centres]]. It was founded in 1964 as \"Society for Radiation\" (Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Strahlenforschung - GSF) and is a joint venture by the [[Federal Ministry of Education and Research (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Education and Research]] and [[ Bavarian State Ministry of Finance and Home]]. \n\n'''Mission'''<br>\n\nThe mission of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is to find new personalized medical solutions for the prevention, diagnosis and therapy of environmentally triggered diseases to promote a healthier society in a rapidly changing world.\n\n'''Management'''<br>\n\n[[Matthias Tsch\u00f6p|Prof. Dr. H. Matthias Tsch\u00f6p]] has been the Scientific Director and Chief Executive Officer of the Center since 2018.\nIn 2019 [[Kerstin G\u00fcnther]] joined the Center and is now the Commercial and Technical Director of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen.\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/about-us/locations/index.html Campus]'''<br>\n\nThe main campus is located in Neuherberg, a district of Oberschlei\u00dfheim, right outside of [[Munich]]\u2019s city borders. The campus has a size of 52.3 hectares. In addition, the Center maintains research facilities inside the city area of Munich, Augsburg, T\u00fcbingen, Hanover, Dresden and Leipzig.\n\n'''Legal form'''<br>\n\nHelmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is a limited liability company according to German law and is financed by a ratio of 90:10 by its two shareholders, the Federal Government and the Free State of Bavaria.\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/helmholtz-zentrum-muenchen/index.html Research Focus]'''<br>\n \nThe Center focuses its research on five key areas:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/metabolic-health/index.html Metabolic Health]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/environmental-health/index.html Environmental Health] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/molecular-targets-therapies/index.html Molecular Targets and Therapies] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/cellprogramming-repair/index.html Cell Programming and Repair] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/bioengineering-digital-health/index.html Bioengineering and Digital Health]\n\n'''[https://www.pioneercampus.org/ The Helmholtz Pioneer Campus] (HPC)'''<br>\n\nThe HPC is an innovation campus where young investigators research for novel solutions in the fields of biomedical sciences, engineering and digitization in the research environment of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen.\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/innovationen/translational-and-clinical-projects/translational-research-centers/index.html Translational and Clinical Projects]'''<br>\n\nTranslational research approaches at the Center are developed in cooperation with clinical partners within a dynamic project portfolio. \n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/idf/index.html Diabetes Study Center]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/ilbd/index.html Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n* [https://www.zaum-online.de/ Center of Allergy and Environment]\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/career/graduates-entry-level-professionals/research/index.html Career development]'''<br>\n\nOne Helmholtz Graduate School (HELENA) in cooperation with the Ludwig Maximilian University Munich (LMU) and the Technical University Munich (TUM) and five Helmholtz Research Schools offer doctoral students in-depth research in the fields of diabetes, lung and radiation research, epigenetics and data science:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-helena.de/ Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health (HELENA)]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-diabetes.org/ International Helmholtz Research School for Diabetes]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-epigenetics.org/ Helmholtz International Epigenetics Research School]\n* [https://www.cpc-researchschool.org/ CPC-Research School Lung Biology and Disease]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/helmholtz-research-school-of-radiation-sciences-rs2/index.html Helmholtz Research School of Radiation Science]\n* [https://www.mu-ds.de/ Munich School for Data Science]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/index.html Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen]\n* [http://www.helmholtz-helena.de Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health ]\n* [http://www.helmholtz.de/en/ Helmholtz Association]\n* [http://www.cpc-munich.org/ Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{coord|48|13|21|N|11|35|36|E|region:DE-BY_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helmholtz Zentrum Munchen}}\n[[Category:Medical research institutes in Germany]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Bavaria]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen''' is a member of the [[Helmholtz Association of German Research Centres]]. It was founded in 1964 as \"Society for Radiation\" (Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Strahlenforschung - GSF) and is a joint venture by the [[Federal Ministry of Education and Research (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Education and Research]] and [[ Bavarian State Ministry of Finance and Home]]. \n\n'''Mission'''<br>\n\nThe mission of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is to find new personalized medical solutions for the prevention, diagnosis and therapy of environmentally triggered diseases to promote a healthier society in a rapidly changing world.\n\n\n'''Management'''<br>\n\n[[Matthias Tsch\u00f6p|Prof. Dr. H. Matthias Tsch\u00f6p]] has been the Scientific Director and Chief Executive Officer of the Center since 2018.\nIn 2019 [[Kerstin G\u00fcnther]] joined the Center and is now the Commercial and Technical Director of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen.\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/about-us/locations/index.html Campus]'''<br>\n\nThe Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen main campus is located in Neuherberg, a district of Oberschlei\u00dfheim, right outside of [[Munich]]\u2019s city borders. The campus has a size of 52.3 hectares. In addition, the Center maintains research facilities inside the city area of Munich, Augsburg, T\u00fcbingen, Hanover, Dresden and Leipzig.\n\n'''Legal form'''<br>\n\nHelmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is a limited liability company according to German law and is financed by a ratio of 90:10 by its two shareholders, the Federal Government and the Free State of Bavaria.\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/helmholtz-zentrum-muenchen/index.html Research Focus]'''<br>\n \nHelmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen focuses its research on five key areas:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/metabolic-health/index.html Metabolic Health]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/environmental-health/index.html Environmental Health] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/molecular-targets-therapies/index.html Molecular Targets and Therapies] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/cellprogramming-repair/index.html Cell Programming and Repair] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/bioengineering-digital-health/index.html Bioengineering and Digital Health]\n\n'''[https://www.pioneercampus.org/ The Helmholtz Pioneer Campus] (HPC)'''<br>\n\nThe HPC is an innovation campus where young investigators research for novel solutions in the fields of biomedical sciences, engineering and digitization in the research environment of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen.\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/innovationen/translational-and-clinical-projects/translational-research-centers/index.html Translational and Clinical Projects]'''<br>\n\nTranslational research approaches at the Center are developed in cooperation with clinical partners within a dynamic project portfolio. \n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/idf/index.html Diabetes Study Center]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/ilbd/index.html Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n* [https://www.zaum-online.de/ Center of Allergy and Environment]\n\n'''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/career/graduates-entry-level-professionals/research/index.html Career development]'''<br>\n\nOne Helmholtz Graduate School (HELENA) in cooperation with the Ludwig Maximilian University Munich (LMU) and the Technical University Munich (TUM) and five Helmholtz Research Schools offer doctoral students in-depth research in the fields of diabetes, lung and radiation research, epigenetics and data science:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-helena.de/ Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health (HELENA)]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-diabetes.org/ International Helmholtz Research School for Diabetes]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-epigenetics.org/ Helmholtz International Epigenetics Research School]\n* [https://www.cpc-researchschool.org/ CPC-Research School Lung Biology and Disease]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/helmholtz-research-school-of-radiation-sciences-rs2/index.html Helmholtz Research School of Radiation Science]\n* [https://www.mu-ds.de/ Munich School for Data Science]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/index.html Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen]\n* [http://www.helmholtz-helena.de Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health ]\n* [http://www.helmholtz.de/en/ Helmholtz Association]\n* [http://www.cpc-munich.org/ Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{coord|48|13|21|N|11|35|36|E|region:DE-BY_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helmholtz Zentrum Munchen}}\n[[Category:Medical research institutes in Germany]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Bavaria]]\n", "name_user": "Ako helmholtz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmholtz_Zentrum_M%C3%BCnchen"}
{"title_page": "International Workshop on Operator Theory and its Applications", "text_new": "'''International Workshop on Operator Theory and its Applications (IWOTA)''' was started in 1981<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news | author = J. W. Helton | title = A conference report | journal = Integral Equations and Operator Theory | volume = 5 | year = 1982 | pages = 605\u2013607 | url=https://link.springer.com/journal/20/5/1/page/2#page-1 }}</ref>  to bring together [[mathematician]]s and [[engineer]]s working in [[operator theory|operator theoretic]] side of [[functional analysis]] and its applications to related fields.<ref name=\"NSF0126746\">{{cite web | title=NSF Award | series=13th International Workshop on Operator Theory and Applications | place=Blacksburg, Virginia | year=2002 | publisher = [[National Science Foundation]] | url = https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0126746&HistoricalAwards=false}}</ref><ref name=\"NSF0536873\">{{cite web | title=NSF Award | series=IWOTA 2005 - International Workshop on Operator Theory and Applications | place=Storrs, CT | year=2005 | publisher = [[National Science Foundation]] | url = https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0536873&HistoricalAwards=false}}</ref>  These include:\n\n* [[Differential equations]] and [[Integral equations]]\n* [[Complex analysis]] and [[Harmonic analysis]]\n* [[Linear system]] and [[Control theory]]\n* [[Mathematical physics]]\n* [[Signal processing]]\n* [[Numerical analysis]]\n\nThe other major branch of [[operator theory]], [[Operator algebras]] (C* and von Neumann Algebras), is not heavily represented at IWOTA and has its own conferences.\n\nIWOTA gathers leading experts from all over the world for an intense exchange of new results, information and opinions, and for tracing the future developments in the field.  The IWOTA meetings provide opportunities for participants (including young [[research]]ers) to present their own work in invited and contributed talks, to interact with other [[research]]ers from around the globe, and to broaden their knowledge of the field.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.ams.org/notices/201501/rnoti-p74.pdf#page=4 | title = Notices of the American Mathematical Society | series = Vol. 62, No. 1 | date = 2015 | page = 4 | publisher = [[American Mathematical Society]] }}</ref> \nIn addition, IWOTA emphasizes cross-disciplinary interaction among [[mathematician]]s, [[Electrical engineering|electrical engineers]] and [[Mathematical physics|mathematical physicists]]. In the even years, the IWOTA workshop is a satellite meeting to the biennial International Symposium on the Mathematical Theory of Networks and Systems (MTNS).<ref name=\"mtns\">{{cite book |editor1=Levan, N. | title=International Symposium on Mathematical Theory of Networks and Systems : August 5-7, 1981, Miramar-Sheraton Hotel, Santa Monica, California | publisher=Western Periodicals Co | location=North Hollywood, California | year=1981 | page=iii | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_rJQAAAAYAAJ }}</ref> From the humble beginnings in the early 80's,<ref name=\":0\" /> the IWOTA workshops grew to become one of the largest continuing conferences attended by the community of researchers in [[operator theory]].<ref name=\"image\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.ilasic.org/IMAGE/IMAGES/image52.pdf#page=35|title = IMAGE, the Bulletin of the International Linear Algebra Society | date=2014| page=35 | publisher=International Linear Algebra Society }}</ref>\n\n==History of IWOTA==\n\n===First IWOTA Meeting===\nThe International Workshop on Operator Theory and its Applications was started on August 1, 1981,<ref name=\":0\" /> adjacent to the International Symposium on Mathematical Theory of Networks and Systems (MTNS)<ref name=\"mtns\" /> with goal of exposing [[operator theory|operator theorists,]] even [[Pure mathematics|pure]] theorists, to recent developments in [[engineering]] (especially ''[[H-infinity methods in control theory]]'') which had a significant intersection with [[operator theory]]. [[Israel Gohberg]] was the visionary and driving force of IWOTA<ref>{{cite book |last=Langer |first=Heinz |editor1 = Bart, Harm | editor2 = Hempfling, Thomas | editor3 = Kaashoek, Marinus A. | title = Israel Gohberg and Friends: On the Occasion of his 80th Birthday|pages=249\u2013252 |chapter=VI.2. The Vienna University of Technology at Vienna, Austria | publisher = [[Birkh\u00e4user | Birkh\u00e4user Verlag]]| location = Basel| isbn = 9783764387334 | chapter-url=https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783764387334 |date=2008-06-23 }}</ref> and president of the IWOTA Steering Committee. From the beginning, J. W. Helton and M. A. Kaashoek served as vice presidents of the steering committee.\n\n===West Meets East===\nBesides the excitement of mathematical discovery over the decades at IWOTA, there was great excitement when the [[Iron Curtain|curtain]] between [[Eastern bloc|Soviet bloc]] and Western operator theorists fell. Until 1990, these two collections of extremely strong mathematicians seldom met due to the tight [[Human rights in the Soviet Union#Freedom of movement|restrictions on travel]] from and in the [[Communist state|communist countries]]. When the [[Iron Curtain|curtain]] dropped, the western mathematicians knew the classic Soviet papers but had a spotty knowledge of much of what else their counterparts were doing.<ref>{{cite book |last=Landau |first=Henry J. |editor1 = Bart, Harm | editor2 = Hempfling, Thomas | editor3 = Kaashoek, Marinus A. | title = Israel Gohberg and Friends: On the Occasion of his 80th Birthday|pages=309\u2013310 |chapter=To Israel |   publisher = [[Birkh\u00e4user | Birkh\u00e4user Verlag]]| location = Basel| isbn = 9783764387334 | chapter-url=https://www.springer.com/us/book/9783764387334 |date=2008-06-23 }}</ref> [[Israel Gohberg|Gohberg]] was one of the operator theorists who knew both sides and he guided IWOTA, a western institution, in bringing (and funding) many prominent [[Post-Soviet states|FSU bloc]] operator theorists to speak at the meetings. As the IWOTA programs demonstrate,<ref name = \"program\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.gmu.ge/iwota2015/Files/Program_IWOTA_2015.pdf | title=IWOTA-2015 Program | date=2015 | publisher=Georgian Mathematical Union, [[Georgian National Academy of Sciences]] }}</ref> this significantly accelerated the cultures' mutual assimilation.<ref>\n{{cite book | editor-last = Dijksma | editor-first = A. | editor2-last = Kaashoek | editor2-first = M.A. | editor3-last = Ran | editor3-first = A.C.M. | title = Recent Advances in Operator Theory | series = Operator Theory: Advances and Applications | volume = 124 | edition = 1 | publisher = [[Birkh\u00e4user | Birkh\u00e4user Verlag]] | location = Basel, Boston, Berlin | pages = xiii\u2013xxii | date = 2001 |isbn = 978-3-0348-9516-3  | issn = 0255-0156 | url=https://books.google.com/?id=Rb4fnwEACAAJ&dq=isbn+9783034895163}}\n</ref>\n\n===Previous IWOTA Meetings===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! #\n! Year \n! Location \n! Chief Organizer(s) \n! Proceedings in OTAA-series<ref name=\"OTAA\">{{cite book | editor-last = Ball | editor-first = J.A. | editor2-last = Dym | editor2-first = H. | editor3-last = Kaashoek | editor3-first = M.A.  | editor4-last = Langer | editor4-first = H. | editor5-last = Tretter| editor5-first = C.|editor5-link= Christiane Tretter | title = Operator Theory: Advances and Applications| series = Series| publisher = [[Birkh\u00e4user | Birkh\u00e4user Verlag]]| location = Basel| issn = 0255-0156| url = https://www.springer.com/series/4850?detailsPage=titles/}}</ref>\n! Participation\n|-\n| 1\t\n| 1981\n| {{flagicon|USA}} Santa Monica, CA, USA\n|  J. W. Helton\n|\n|<math>\\pm</math>40\n|-\n| 2\n| 1983\n| {{flagicon|Israel}} Rehovot, Israel\n| H. Dym, I. Gohberg{{efn-lr|Israel Gohberg died on 12 October 2009.<ref name=\"IG\">{{cite news | author1 =  A. E. Frazho | author2 =  M. A. Kaashoek | author3 = L. Rodman | title = Israel Gohberg [Obituary] | journal = IEEE 